(("Television, radio and TV coverage | guardian.co.uk" "Latest news and features from guardian.co.uk, the world's leading liberal voice" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio" (20852 16600 941068) feed 0 nil nil ((title nil "Television, radio and TV coverage | guardian.co.uk") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio") (description nil "Latest news and features from guardian.co.uk, the world's leading liberal voice") (language nil "en-gb") (copyright nil "Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. 2013") (lastBuildDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 14:15:34 GMT") (docs nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/webfeeds") (ttl nil "15") (image nil (title nil "Television, radio and TV coverage | guardian.co.uk") (url nil "http://image.guardian.co.uk/sitecrumbs/Guardian.gif") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) (item nil (title nil "Is there too much historical fantasy on screen?") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/da-vincis-demons-too-much-historical-fantasy") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/97248?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ada-vincis-demons-too-much-historical-fantasy%3A1896371&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Historical+drama+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CFox+%28TV+network%29%2CGame+of+Thrones+%28TV+series%29%2CTelevision+industry+%28Media%29%2CUS+television+industry%2CMedia%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CUS+Elections%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Sarah+Hughes&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+12%3A35&c8=1896371&c9=Article&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Da+Vinci%27s+Demons%3A+is+there+too+much+historical+fantasy+on+screen%3F&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FHistorical+drama\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The eight-part drama starts tonight on Fox with Leonardo as a sword-wielding rogue. Later in the year sees a new version of The Three Musketeers, plus several pirate dramas and  other historical epics. Is it all too much swashbuckling and sorcery?</p><p>The problem with a show becoming a hit is that suddenly every one else wants a piece of the action. Thus, after <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/lost\" title=\"\">Lost</a>, we were inundated with overly complex dramas filled with secrets and cryptic clues (Flash Forward, The Event, Alcatraz); without <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/mad-men-tv-series\" title=\"\">Mad Men</a>'s Emmy success, it is unlikely networks would have been desperate to commission either Pan Am or The Playboy Club.&nbsp;And now,&nbsp;thanks to the success of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/game-of-thrones\" title=\"\">Game of Thrones</a>, viewers are being treated to a whole raft of historical fantasy shows.</p><p>Take <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2013/apr/16/da-vincis-demons-reinvents-leonardo\" title=\"\">Da Vinci's Demons</a>, which starts on Fox this evening. The eight-part drama recasts the renaissance artist Leonardo da Vinci as a charming rogue with an eye for the ladies, often seen flashing his chest while fending off assorted enemies. Or the new version of the Three Musketeers, coming to the BBC next year, starring Peter Capaldi as Cardinal Richelieu and Skins actor Luke Pasqualino as D'Artagnan. Sorcery and swordplay, it seems, will become even harder to escape from the schedules.</p><p>Elsewhere, US TV networks have two pirate dramas in the mix: Black Sails, a Treasure Island prequel in which, <a href=\"http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/michael-bays-black-sails-trailer-441447\" title=\"\">judging by the eight-minute trailer</a>, Michael Bay indulges his twin desires to watch women kissing and blow things up a lot, and Crossbones, which stars John Malkovich as Blackbeard and is scripted by Luther's Neil Cross. Meanwhile, a big-budget version look at the life of Marco Polo produced by Harvey Weinstein is in the works at American cable channel Starz.</p><p>Over here, the BBC has clearly decided that the best way to imitate Game of Thrones's blend of backstabbing and betrayal is to strip away the fantasy trappings and head back to George R R Martin's original inspiration: the <a href=\"http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1496\" title=\"\">War of the Roses.</a></p><p>Later this year they will air <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yPBg9KK3gYo\" title=\"\">The White Queen</a>, a 10-part adaptation of Philippa Gregory's War of the Roses-set novel. That will be followed in 2014 by the much-anticipated BBC take on <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/hilary-mantel\" title=\"\">Hilary Mantel</a>'s Wolf Hall starring Mark Rylance as arch-conspirator Thomas Cromwell.</p><p>Yet, while it is easy to understand the rush to imitate the hugely successful Game of Thrones, do we really want to be subsumed in a sea of historical fantasy? As someone who owns a much-cherished box set of Sean Bean's Napoleonic war series <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5C8IuThoWuU\" title=\"\">Sharpe</a>, I'm always open to a certain amount of swashbuckling and bodice ripping. But even the biggest fan can worry that the bandwagon may be in danger of tipping.&nbsp;</p><p>With Da Vinci's Demons,&nbsp;it soon becomes clear that it's not quite as clever as Game of Thrones which is a great shame because in its better bits – the throwaway one-liners, the mischievous playing with history – Da Vinci's Demons feels a little like Sherlock or Merlin in tone (and it is no surprise to note that it is a BBC Worldwide co-production). It is a show that should work as&nbsp;great,&nbsp;blockbuster family entertainment but is instead trying too hard to be dark and edgy and adult.</p><p>But what do you think – will you be watching Da Vinci's Demons? Which of the other new shows would you watch? Can anyone replicate the success of Game of Thrones? And is there really room in your life for two pirate dramas? As ever let me know in the comments below …</p><p><em>Da Vinci's Demons starts on Fox tonight at 10pm.</em></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/historical-drama\">Historical drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/fox\">Fox</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/game-of-thrones\">Game of Thrones</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/television\">Television industry</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/ustelevision\">US television industry</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/sarahhughes\">Sarah Hughes</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Historical drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Fox") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Game of Thrones") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Television industry") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "US television industry") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 11:35:28 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/da-vincis-demons-too-much-historical-fantasy") (dc:creator nil "Sarah Hughes") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T11:35:28Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407507046") (media:keywords nil "Historical drama, Television, Drama, Fox, Game of Thrones, Television industry, US television industry, Media, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366370453802/Tom-Riley-as-Leonardo-Da--005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Greg Wiliiams/FOX") (media:description nil "Tom Riley as Leonardo Da Vinci in Da Vinci's Demons. Photograph: Greg Wiliiams/FOX")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366370461494/Tom-Riley-as-Leonardo-Da--010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Greg Wiliiams/FOX") (media:description nil "Tom Riley as Leonardo Da Vinci in Da Vinci's Demons. Photograph: Greg Wiliiams/FOX"))) (item nil (title nil "Last night's TV") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/19/brushing-up-on-british-tunnels") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/55738?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Abrushing-up-on-british-tunnels%3A1896130&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=G2&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CDanny+Baker%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Sam+Wollaston&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+07%3A00&c8=1896130&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Last+nights+TV+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Brushing+Up+On+%E2%80%93+British+Tunnels%3B+Maureen+Lipman%3A+If+Memory+Serves+Me+Right%3B+Could+We+Survive+a+Mega-Tsunami%3F+%E2%80%93+TV+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">We're in a tunnel, being splurt-blasted by Danny Baker's words and wit and wisdom …</p><p>The most entertaining programme on TV last night? Easy: <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s1c4y\" title=\"Brushing Up On\"><strong>Brushing Up On&nbsp;–</strong></a> (BBC4). Brushing up on what? Tunnels, obviously: something, says presenter Danny Baker, all human beings are obsessed with. I'd like to have sat in on the meeting at which this one got commissioned (if that's how these things happen). So, Danny, you want to make a programme about tunnels? Like a documentary, but not really a documentary, because you're not finding anything out, or doing any reporting? And although there is a factual element to it, some of these facts have no basis in truth and are quite clearly plucked from your (over) vivid imagination? More like standup than documentary, then. Tunnel-based comedy, hmmm …</p><p>On the plus side, you don't need to go anywhere, apart from the BBC archive to dig out some old footage of tunnels and people tunneling, around which you can twist your tale. And toss in a few cheap graphics. It's only going to cost about a 140 quid to make, including your fee. You know what, let's do it!</p><p>I imagine that's how it went. In which case that commissioning editor is a bit of a hero, because the result is a little treat. The story of the Channel tunnel starts in 1802 with Napoleon, who was going to build an island (like Boris's) halfway across. It ends in 1990 with a man whose name (Graham) came out of the (hard) hat; he got to go through the hole to meet the Frenchman (Phillippe) who had been digging from the other side. In the 188 years in between, there's plenty of xenophobia; a man in a suit who trips up again and again; a comedy Frenchman saying \"bonjour\"; a machine that digs itself into a hole, dies, and then gets bought for £20,000 by a man named Ron; and&nbsp;more.</p><p>It's not just about the Channel tunnel, though. It's about hot Irish men, \"with iron in their arms and their buttocks\", building the London underground. It's about the tunnels under the Thames, and Swampy, and David Bellamy, and badgers, and a man named Don who watches the badgers.</p><p>It doesn't all work. At times it's hard even to know what Baker is on about. Some of it I think might actually be wrong (like the Dartford tunnel may have two lanes but these days they both head north, so, contrary to what DB says, the only way IS Essex). Who cares though, because so much of it is a joy. The word \"buttocks\" IS funny, as are men called Ron and Don; though not as funny as a man in a suit tripping over, on repeat; and the sentence: \"So you'd recommend fish-farming in a German war tunnel, then?\" from some old footage from the Channel Islands, is one of the greatest ever uttered.</p><p>It comes out so fast too. It's as if there's a fire hydrant on Baker's forehead, it's turned on full, connected to a high pressure hose and aimed at you, and you're being splurt-blasted by his words and wit and wisdom. No, maybe not wisdom. Imagination, then, and a lot of weird stuff, some of which is about tunnels. Fabulous. Bring on the bridges next week.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s0zvx\" title=\"Maureen Lipman: If Memory Serves Me Right\"><strong>Maureen Lipman: If Memory Serves Me Right</strong></a> (BBC1) was one of those documentaries that involves a non-expert celebrity going on a journey of discovery triggered partly by events in their own lives. You know the ones. So Maureen's finding out about memory, partly because her father lost his, and she's worried about hers. There's a bit of science, a bit of psychology, a bit of Paul McKenna, quite a lot of blah. She's amiable company, but the film is meandering, inconclusive, unmemorable.</p><p>And <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s0zqv\" title=\"Could We Survive a Mega-Tsunami?\"><strong>Could We Survive a Mega-Tsunami?</strong></a> (BBC2) was one of those what-if documentaries (thankfully, no lame drama element to this one: they're the worst). In fact, more of a what-when one, because this is going to happen. There's going to be a volcanic eruption and half of La Palma, one of the Canary islands, is going to slide into the sea. No great shame, you might think, but this will unleash a massive CGI wave three times the height of the Shard that will take out New York just like in The Day After Tomorrow, though less convincingly because this CGI wave doesn't have a Hollywood budget behind it.</p><p>They're screwed then, over there. What about us, though? Well, not great if you're in Penzance, I'm afraid. Brighton? Touch and go. But tucked away snuggly and smuggly round the corner here in London? I'll be fine, thank you.</p><p><a href=\"http://gu.com/p/3f8h9/tw via @guardian\" title=\" Watch this: TV highlights\">• Watch this: TV highlights</a></p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://tvlistings.guardian.co.uk/default.aspx\" title=\" Full TV listings\">• Full TV listings</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/danny-baker\">Danny Baker</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/samwollaston\">Sam Wollaston</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 20