along comes the scene where Spartacus slices the entire front of someone's head off. That's variety for you.</p><p>While it wouldn't have been made were it not for the success of <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ol67qo3WhJk\" title=\"Gladiator\">Gladiator</a> and <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wDiUG52ZyHQ\" title=\"300\">300</a>, Spartacus ended up outclassing those high-grossing movies in almost every department, save popularity. The virtue of the long-form storytelling (39 episodes in all) is that even when a minor character dies it has the impact of losing, if not an old friend, then at least a long-term acquaintance. And the finale must be one of the most emotionally violent ever televised, with a message, <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SYRGF0GWTD4\" title=\"delivered in Spartacuss pre-battle speech\">delivered in Spartacus's pre-battle speech</a>, that rings through the ages as he fights for those \"forced to toil and suffer while those in coin and position see their fortunes grow beyond need or purpose.\" 'Twas ever thus.</p><p>The Starz Channel's Spartacus is one of the TV highpoints of recent years – or at least it would be considered so, had it gathered more viewers. It may yet be regarded as such, for if there was ever a show that benefited from the boxset format, it's Spartacus. Watch a few episodes. If you don't like it then watch a couple more, because when it takes, you'll be gripped and put through the wringer.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/spartacus\">Spartacus</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/historical-drama\">Historical drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/phelimoneill\">Phelim O'Neill</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Spartacus") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Historical drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 14:00:02 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/18/spartacus-box-set-review") (dc:creator nil "Phelim O'Neill") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T23:06:13Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407442691") (media:keywords nil "Spartacus, Historical drama, Television, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366290155216/Spartacus-War-of-the-Damn-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Starz Entertainment, LLC") (media:description nil "Liam McIntyre and blood brothers and sisters in Spartacus: War of the Damned. Photograph: Starz Entertainment, LLC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/18/1366290161321/Spartacus-War-of-the-Damn-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Starz Entertainment, LLC") (media:description nil "Liam McIntyre and blood brothers and sisters in Spartacus: War of the Damned. Photograph: Starz Entertainment, LLC")))) ("The return of The Fried Chicken Shop" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/33942?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Areturn-of-fried-chicken-shop%3A1895793&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CDocumentary+%28TV+genre%29%2CFactual+TV+%28TV+genre%29%2CFast+food+%28life+and+style%29%2CFood+and+drink++%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CFood+and+Drink&c6=Stuart+Heritage&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+01%3A10&c8=1895793&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+return+of+The+Fried+Chicken+Shop&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The highly entertaining look at life in a London takeaway is coming back to Channel 4 for three new episodes. If they are as good as the first documentary, we are in for a treat</p><p>In February, Channel 4 aired <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-fried-chicken-shop-life-in-a-day\" title=\"\">The Fried Chicken Shop</a>, a one-off documentary set in a London fried chicken shop. Using the same fixed-rig setup that the channel loves to return to again and again, The Fried Chicken Shop took a week's worth of footage from Clapham's Roosters Spot eatery and distilled it into a tightly packed hour of entertainment. And it was much more fun than it had any right to be.</p><p></p><p>This week, Channel 4 announced that The Fried Chicken Shop is to return for three episodes that will repeat and expand on the premise of the original. We will still see the Roosters Spot staff grind out one impossibly long shift after another. We will still see Clapham's finest slumped over the counter at chucking-out time, manfully attempting to order a Mega Mix chicken burger with their last remaining molecule of dignity intact. But this time, we are promised, we will also get to follow some of the takeaway customers home. This new addition will almost certainly contain the most exciting footage of a lonely man sitting on a carpet in a bedsit and silently eating chips at 2am that British television has ever seen.</p><p></p><p>The beauty of The Fried Chicken Shop is its universality. You might watch <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/24-hours-in-ae\" title=\"\">24 Hours in A&E</a> and feel admiration for the medical staff and their ability to maintain composure under extraordinary pressure. You might watch <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-hotel\" title=\"\">The Hotel</a> and wonder why any of the guests agreed to let cameras into their rooms. But to watch The Fried Chicken Shop is to recognise a part of yourself.</p><p></p><p>Plenty of us, at one point or another, have bought fast food while drunk. Many of us will have done so without a second thought for the staff behind the counter. What The Fried Chicken Shop did so well was to make it clear how awful we probably are when we do this.  Judging by the show, the staff of Roosters Spot have put up with it all: aggressive drunks; attention-seeking drunks; people pretending to be disabled; drug dealers handing out business cards; and social media hipster dullards, who function as an argument for sawing a circle around the edge of London and letting it drop into the sea.</p><p></p><p>Watching the staff remain as good-natured and professional as they were in the face of such soul-sapping arsery was a joy. It was as heartwarming as anything else I have seen on television this year. And although it had the potential to lapse into the uncomfortably sneery classism that Channel 4's Gypsy programmes sometimes revel in, The Fried Chicken Shop staunchly refused to judge anyone. It didn't have a point to make, or an issue to force home, other than the awkward \"Wow, don't people eat a lot of chicken these days?\" message tacked on to the start. It was happy enough just to show us the chicken shop and let us reach our own conclusions. The first episode was magnificent. I can't wait to hang out there again.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/documentary\">Documentary</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/factual-tv\">Factual TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/fast-food\">Fast food</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink\">Food & drink</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/stuart-heritage\">Stuart Heritage</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/return-of-fried-chicken-shop" (20847 58009) old 10 nil nil ((title nil "The return of The Fried Chicken Shop") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/return-of-fried-chicken-shop") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/33942?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Areturn-of-fried-chicken-shop%3A1895793&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CDocumentary+%28TV+genre%29%2CFactual+TV+%28TV+genre%29%2CFast+food+%28life+and+style%29%2CFood+and+drink++%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CFood+and+Drink&c6=Stuart+Heritage&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+01%3A10&c8=1895793&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost%2CFeature&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+return+of+The+Fried+Chicken+Shop&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The highly entertaining look at life in a London takeaway is coming back to Channel 4 for three new episodes. If they are as good as the first documentary, we are in for a treat</p><p>In February, Channel 4 aired <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-fried-chicken-shop-life-in-a-day\" title=\"\">The Fried Chicken Shop</a>, a one-off documentary set in a London fried chicken shop. Using the same fixed-rig setup that the channel loves to return to again and again, The Fried Chicken Shop took a week's worth of footage from Clapham's Roosters Spot eatery and distilled it into a tightly packed hour of entertainment. And it was much more fun than it had any right to be.</p><p></p><p>This week, Channel 4 announced that The Fried Chicken Shop is to return for three episodes that will repeat and expand on the premise of the original. We will still see the Roosters Spot staff grind out one impossibly long shift after another. We will still see Clapham's finest slumped over the counter at chucking-out time, manfully attempting to order a Mega Mix chicken burger with their last remaining molecule of dignity intact. But this time, we are promised, we will also get to follow some of the takeaway customers home. This new addition will almost certainly contain the most exciting footage of a lonely man sitting on a carpet in a bedsit and silently eating chips at 2am that British television has ever seen.</p><p></p><p>The beauty of The Fried Chicken Shop is its universality. You might watch <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/24-hours-in-ae\" title=\"\">24 Hours in A&E</a> and feel admiration for the medical staff and their ability to maintain composure under extraordinary pressure. You might watch <a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/the-hotel\" title=\"\">The Hotel</a> and wonder why any of the guests agreed to let cameras into their rooms. But to watch The Fried Chicken Shop is to recognise a part of yourself.</p><p></p><p>Plenty of us, at one point or another, have bought fast food while drunk. Many of us will have done so without a second thought for the staff behind the counter. What The Fried Chicken Shop did so well was to make it clear how awful we probably are when we do this.  Judging by the show, the staff of Roosters Spot have put up with it all: aggressive drunks; attention-seeking drunks; people pretending to be disabled; drug dealers handing out business cards; and social media hipster dullards, who function as an argument for sawing a circle around the edge of London and letting it drop into the sea.</p><p></p><p>Watching the staff remain as good-natured and professional as they were in the face of such soul-sapping arsery was a joy. It was as heartwarming as anything else I have seen on television this year. And although it had the potential to lapse into the uncomfortably sneery classism that Channel 4's Gypsy programmes sometimes revel in, The Fried Chicken Shop staunchly refused to judge anyone. It didn't have a point to make, or an issue to force home, other than the awkward \"Wow, don't people eat a lot of chicken these days?\" message tacked on to the start. It was happy enough just to show us the chicken shop and let us reach our own conclusions. The first episode was magnificent. I can't wait to hang out there again.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/documentary\">Documentary</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/factual-tv\">Factual TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/fast-food\">Fast food</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink\">Food & drink</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/stuart-heritage\">Stuart Heritage</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Documentary") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Factual TV") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Fast food") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Food & drink") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Life and style") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 12:10:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/return-of-fried-chicken-shop") (dc:creator nil "Stuart Heritage") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T12:10:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407435148") (media:keywords nil "Television, Television & radio, Documentary, Factual TV, Fast food, Food & drink, Life and style") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366284559725/The-Fried-Chicken-Shop-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Staff at Roosters Spot, the subject of Channel 4's The Fried Chicken Shop, which is to return for three new episodes.")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366284566906/The-Fried-Chicken-Shop-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Staff at Roosters Spot, the subject of Channel 4's The Fried Chicken Shop, which is to return for three new episodes.")))) ("Why is EastEnders so bad?" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/26566?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Awhy-is-eastenders-so-bad%3A1895696&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=EastEnders%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CSoap+opera+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Television+Media%2CTV&c6=Homa+Khaleeli&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+11%3A27&c8=1895696&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Why+is+EastEnders+so+bad%3F&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FEastEnders\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The soap's ratings have been sliding for more than a year – and a host of major characters have quit the square. What can it do to win back disgruntled fans?</p><p>There is a problem on the Square. Sure, there have been the usual tear-stained wedding dramas, squalling rows in the Queen Vic and near-incestuous couplings, but something is wrong: E20 has lost its edge. <a href=\"http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eastenders-facing-ratings-crisis-angry-1771100\" title=\"\">Ratings have been on the slide for more than a year</a>, while forums have been filling up with disgruntled fans. To put it like a Walford local: wossgaoinon?</p><p>Well, for a start, there are the recycled storylines. It's been a staggering 20 years since the angry baby that is Phil Mitchell first seduced his brother's breathy wife Sharon. Now, like a market-stall knockoff of Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton, <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2310171/EastEnders-Phil-Mitchell-finally-gets-girl-Sharon-Rickman-succumbs-brutish-charms.html?ito=feeds-newsxml\" title=\"\">they are at it again for a third time</a>. It's a plot so lacking in excitement that on Monday night, the cliffhanger ending was Sharon's six-year-old son (complete with Ann Widdecombe haircut) threatening to run away from home.</p><p>Stuck in a similarly boring rut are Max and Tanya, who have also been splitting up and getting back together on a loop since they first arrived in Walford, the London borough where marriages go to die. After several affairs, attempted murders and short-lived relationships with other people, Max has left Tanya once more – this time for Kirsty, whose larger-than-life lips, eyelashes and hair extensions have been stuck on in place of a personality. But inevitably Max is yet again pining after Tanya – a situation so predictable even the couple's children merely roll their eyes in response.</p><p>On top of this there are the non-plots – actual screen time was devoted to discovering who had stolen Dot's cold cuts from the fridge. And then there are the really unbelievable ones. Such as Masood, the square's nicest father figure, dating 19-year-old Ayesha, before the writers shamefacedly let it fizzle out. To cheer us up,  they've since put together attractive Denise and slimy egomaniac Ian Beale as the square's supposedly hilarious odd couple. But seeing as the soap operates a strict looks-blind policy to casting – with Phil Mitchell and Max as the square studs while Ray has been confined to the Fox sisters – it's hardly the most shocking of hookups.</p><p>Despite a cull of characters last year (I am still in mourning for the loss of <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2248900/Nina-Wadia-quits-EastEnders-years-playing-Zainab-Masood.html\" title=\"\">Zainab Masood</a>), Eastenders still has some great ones – Kim is hilarious, Shirley does tough vulnerability brilliantly, and Kat and Alfie still have an impressive amount of chemistry. But instead of giving them some depth and storylines to progress with, there has been an emphasis on bringing back old favourites to bring back some sparks. When in truth, we don't want the same old faces but some new plotlines to put the drama back in to the doof doof endings.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/eastenders\">EastEnders</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/soap-opera\">Soap opera</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/homa-khaleeli\">Homa Khaleeli</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/why-is-eastenders-so-bad" (20847 51847) old 4 nil nil ((title nil "Why is EastEnders so bad?") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/why-is-eastenders-so-bad") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/26566?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Awhy-is-eastenders-so-bad%3A1895696&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=EastEnders%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CSoap+opera+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Television+Media%2CTV&c6=Homa+Khaleeli&c7=2013%2F04%2F18+11%3A27&c8=1895696&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Why+is+EastEnders+so+bad%3F&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FEastEnders\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The soap's ratings have been sliding for more than a year – and a host of major characters have quit the square. What can it do to win back disgruntled fans?</p><p>There is a problem on the Square. Sure, there have been the usual tear-stained wedding dramas, squalling rows in the Queen Vic and near-incestuous couplings, but something is wrong: E20 has lost its edge. <a href=\"http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/eastenders-facing-ratings-crisis-angry-1771100\" title=\"\">Ratings have been on the slide for more than a year</a>, while forums have been filling up with disgruntled fans. To put it like a Walford local: wossgaoinon?</p><p>Well, for a start, there are the recycled storylines. It's been a staggering 20 years since the angry baby that is Phil Mitchell first seduced his brother's breathy wife Sharon. Now, like a market-stall knockoff of Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton, <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2310171/EastEnders-Phil-Mitchell-finally-gets-girl-Sharon-Rickman-succumbs-brutish-charms.html?ito=feeds-newsxml\" title=\"\">they are at it again for a third time</a>. It's a plot so lacking in excitement that on Monday night, the cliffhanger ending was Sharon's six-year-old son (complete with Ann Widdecombe haircut) threatening to run away from home.</p><p>Stuck in a similarly boring rut are Max and Tanya, who have also been splitting up and getting back together on a loop since they first arrived in Walford, the London borough where marriages go to die. After several affairs, attempted murders and short-lived relationships with other people, Max has left Tanya once more – this time for Kirsty, whose larger-than-life lips, eyelashes and hair extensions have been stuck on in place of a personality. But inevitably Max is yet again pining after Tanya – a situation so predictable even the couple's children merely roll their eyes in response.</p><p>On top of this there are the non-plots – actual screen time was devoted to discovering who had stolen Dot's cold cuts from the fridge. And then there are the really unbelievable ones. Such as Masood, the square's nicest father figure, dating 19-year-old Ayesha, before the writers shamefacedly let it fizzle out. To cheer us up,  they've since put together attractive Denise and slimy egomaniac Ian Beale as the square's supposedly hilarious odd couple. But seeing as the soap operates a strict looks-blind policy to casting – with Phil Mitchell and Max as the square studs while Ray has been confined to the Fox sisters – it's hardly the most shocking of hookups.</p><p>Despite a cull of characters last year (I am still in mourning for the loss of <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2248900/Nina-Wadia-quits-EastEnders-years-playing-Zainab-Masood.html\" title=\"\">Zainab Masood</a>), Eastenders still has some great ones – Kim is hilarious, Shirley does tough vulnerability brilliantly, and Kat and Alfie still have an impressive amount of chemistry. But instead of giving them some depth and storylines to progress with, there has been an emphasis on bringing back old favourites to bring back some sparks. When in truth, we don't want the same old faces but some new plotlines to put the drama back in to the doof doof endings.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/eastenders\">EastEnders</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/soap-opera\">Soap opera</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/homa-khaleeli\">Homa Khaleeli</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "EastEnders") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Soap opera") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Blogposts") (pubDate nil "Thu, 18 Apr 2013 10:27:19 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2013/apr/18/why-is-eastenders-so-bad") (dc:creator nil "Homa Khaleeli") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-18T11:18:56Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407427102") (media:keywords nil "EastEnders, Television, Drama, Soap opera") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366279202222/EastEnders---third-time-l-004.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC/Kieron McCarron") (media:description nil "EastEnders … third time lucky for Phil and Sharon? Photograph: BBC/Kieron McCarron")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/18/1366279210312/EastEnders---third-time-l-009.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "BBC/Kieron McCarron") (media:description nil "EastEnders … third time lucky for Phil and Sharon? Photograph: BBC/Kieron McCarron")))) ("Martin and Gary Kemp: 'We complement each other'" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/3986?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amartin-gary-kemp-spandau-ballet%3A1894802&ch=Life+and+style&c3=Guardian&c4=Family+%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style%2CMusic%2CPop+and+rock+%28Music+genre%29%2CCulture%2CFilm%2CEastEnders%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CSoap+opera+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Pop+Music%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CFamily+and+Relationships%2CTV&c6=Nick+Duerden&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+03%3A00&c8=1894802&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CInterview&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Martin+and+Gary+Kemp%3A+%27We+complement+each+other%27&c66=Life+and+style&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FLife+and+style%2FLife+and+style%2FFamily\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">They went from being new romantics in Spandau Ballet to playing London gangsters in the film The Krays. Now the brothers are about to appear on TV together again</p><p>An enduring tale of sibling harmony, Gary and Martin Kemp have spent decades working companionably alongside one another without ever, publicly at least, succumbing to fraternal combustion. The arts, and particularly pop music, is&nbsp;littered with brothers (more so, curiously, than sisters) who have tried to do the same and failed, among them Ray and Dave Davies of the Kinks and Noel and Liam Gallagher of Oasis, each undone by ego and the need to dominate. But the Kemps are different, an anomaly. Now&nbsp;both in their 50s, they remain essentially one and the same, and consequently stronger together than the sum of their parts.</p><p>But how? Gary Kemp, who, at 53, is two years Martin's senior, thinks that it is down to their upbringing. \"There were only four of us in our family: my mum, my dad, me, him. They were devoted to us, and we were devoted to&nbsp;them. It was them that gave us our sense of responsibility to one another, our moral compass. We've never lost it.\"</p><p>Initially, they were both child actors, often being cast alongside one another. Then, in the late 70s, they formed Spandau Ballet, new romantic goliaths with an unusual sense of fashion and a gift for mainstream balladry. The band ultimately split acrimoniously, but the Kemp brothers' partnership remained intact and, in 1990, they revived their first love, acting, playing Reg and Ronnie Kray in The Krays. They have dabbled in music and acting ever since, sometimes apart, more frequently in&nbsp;tandem.</p><p>This month, they return to the small screen, fronting the documentary Gangs of Britain, in which they explore British gang culture past and present. As ever, they make a good team, but do they never get sick of working with each other? Do they not crave a little autonomy?</p><p>Gary smiles. \"Not really, no, because we get on, we complement each other. Also, we're different people, with different personalities. What Martin does, I would never attempt, and vice versa, I think.\"</p><p>Is this true? To the viewing public at least, this is less clear. Surely casting directors could request either of them?</p><p>Gary remains insistent. \"No really, we are completely different. I'm more hyper, he is more laidback. I'm a control freak, I've always lusted for cultural things. Martin is more physical, more charismatic.\"</p><p>\"Charisma always was the important thing to me,\" Martin says. \"I joined Spandau Ballet not because I wanted to be the best musician in the world, but because I wanted to be Elvis Presley, Marlon Brando.\"</p><p>\"Sexual attraction,\" Gary suggests.</p><p>Martin chuckles. \"Yes,\" he says. \"I&nbsp;wanted that.\"</p><p>When I meet the Kemps in their PR offices, both look immaculate: suited and booted, hair swept back, their jawlines, up close, improbably strong. Gary is, indeed, the more hyper, the more effusive, while Martin has clearly learned plenty from watching Brando. Sitting in a large armchair that seems too small for him, and interlocking his fingers, he doesn't say much, but instead broods with a quiet intensity.</p><p>They were born and brought up in Islington, north London. Their father was a printer, their mother a seamstress, and they were latchkey children who joined a drama club for want of anything better to do after school. But in the 60s, the local Anna Scher children's theatre drama club was to British television what the Brit School is to today's pop charts: a conveyor belt of readymade talent. They were soon appearing in children's TV programmes and small films. At 16, Gary, a Bowie obsessive, started a band, and when they required a new bassist, he asked Martin not because Martin had any musical prowess – he hadn't – but because \"he was the coolest guy we knew, always popular with the girls. If anyone was going to get us magazine front covers, it was him.\"</p><p>Alongside Duran Duran, Spandau Ballet dominated the early 80s with their flash swagger, but success was tempered by boiling backroom rivalries. \"Me and Martin would fight occasionally, sure,\" Gary says, \"but no&nbsp;one could ever take sides because it&nbsp;would blow over in no time. If I argued with Tony [Hadley, the lead singer], on the other hand, it would be a disaster. It could have gone on for weeks – for ever.\"</p><p>\"It did,\" says Martin, laughing.</p><p>Band harmony ruptured, seemingly irrevocably, in the late 80s, but when the band finally split in 1990, the Kemps landed on their feet. That same&nbsp;year, the film The Krays established their acting careers, though neither achieved as much big-screen success in its wake as they had hoped. In the mid-90s, Gary decamped to Los Angeles to give Hollywood a go. Martin soon followed. \"We were going up for the same auditions a lot of the time, obviously,\" Martin says, \"but we understood that; there was no getting around it.\"</p><p>Nevertheless, they did try, by having separate agents. \"But,\" says Gary, \"sometimes Martin would get a script I&nbsp;hadn't been sent, and it was difficult not to phone my agent and say, 'Hey, he's got it, why haven't I?'\"</p><p></p><p>Both returned to the UK, and in 1998 Martin landed a major role in EastEnders. I ask how Gary felt about this and he tells me I'm forgetting something. Three years earlier, Martin had been diagnosed with a brain tumour – two, in fact. \"It was a terrible time. I felt awful for him, and so guilty. I was the older brother, and here he was with this terrible disease, not me. So when he got better and landed EastEnders, all I felt was pride and relief.\"</p><p>\"That was the main reason I took the part,\" Martin says. \"I'd had three years of illness. I needed to change that, to leave that part of my life behind.\"</p><p>In January 2009, illness tested them again when they lost both parents within four days of one another. \"An absolute disaster,\" Gary says. Their mother had been sick, and was in hospital for a heart operation. The family visited her one day, but by the time they got home, their father was behaving strangely. Complaining of a whooshing in his ear, he said he needed the toilet. \"He was in there a long time. I called out to him, and he said: 'I'm all right, boy.' But his voice sounded strange.\"</p><p>He had had a massive heart attack. Moments later, Gary was in the bathroom giving his father the kiss of life. He died a few days later. Telling their mother was the hardest thing he has ever had to do. \"She simply didn't want to live. She gave up.\"</p><p>But in this decision, he says, there was a kind of solace, peace, even. \"Our parents had never spent a day apart. They were so devoted, so old-fashioned, really. With him gone, she was lost. She looked around her and said: 'All is fine.' What she meant was, my wife was about to have a baby, Spandau were getting back together again after 19 years, and she was confident that both me and Martin were happy. So she was right, everything was fine, and she could go. Two days later, she was gone. We had a joint funeral.\"</p><p>Today, Gary lives in central London with his second wife. He has four sons. Martin and his wife live in Herefordshire with one daughter and one son. Their families socialise a lot, and the brothers will continue to work together. They would like to do more documentaries, and are in discussion to co-direct a film. The union has been fruitful so far, why stop now?</p><p>\"Mum and Dad were fantastic parents, and they instilled a lot of pride in us, a lot of love,\" says Gary. Martin nods solemnly. \"We've taken a lot from them, I think,\" he says. \"Me and Gary, the way we are – it's all down to them.\"</p><p></p><p><em>• </em><a href=\"http://www.crimeandinvestigation.co.uk/shows/gangs-of-britain.html\" title=\"\"><em>Gangs of Britain</em></a><em> begins on the Crime & Investigation Network, Sky Channel 553 at 9pm on 21 April</em></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/family\">Family</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/popandrock\">Pop and rock</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/eastenders\">EastEnders</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/soap-opera\">Soap opera</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/nick-duerden\">Nick Duerden</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2013/apr/19/martin-gary-kemp-spandau-ballet" (20849 19940) old 3 nil nil ((title nil "Martin and Gary Kemp: 'We complement each other'") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2013/apr/19/martin-gary-kemp-spandau-ballet") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/3986?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amartin-gary-kemp-spandau-ballet%3A1894802&ch=Life+and+style&c3=Guardian&c4=Family+%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style%2CMusic%2CPop+and+rock+%28Music+genre%29%2CCulture%2CFilm%2CEastEnders%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CSoap+opera+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Pop+Music%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CFamily+and+Relationships%2CTV&c6=Nick+Duerden&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+03%3A00&c8=1894802&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CInterview&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Martin+and+Gary+Kemp%3A+%27We+complement+each+other%27&c66=Life+and+style&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FLife+and+style%2FLife+and+style%2FFamily\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">They went from being new romantics in Spandau Ballet to playing London gangsters in the film The Krays. Now the brothers are about to appear on TV together again</p><p>An enduring tale of sibling harmony, Gary and Martin Kemp have spent decades working companionably alongside one another without ever, publicly at least, succumbing to fraternal combustion. The arts, and particularly pop music, is&nbsp;littered with brothers (more so, curio