and on the planet are a few adorable trundling robots rather than a self-supporting village for wannabe space celebrities.</p><p></p><p>Let's assume, though, that the contestants get there (after eight years of rigorous training), and can breathe and eat. They'll suffer constant video surveillance in a hostile environment, but then so do millions of Londoners. But what if they fall ill? Even if the producers make sure one of the contestants is a doctor, a single doctor can't be a specialist in everything. So it would probably be better if they were all doctors. Then the show could be sold as a kind of real-life Grey's Anatomy in space, with the inevitable low-gravity loving.</p><p>Cultural puritans might denounce the whole idea as a perverse extreme of reality TV, which in its Big Brother incarnation – a format also invented by the Dutch – was always designed primarily as a form of psychological torture for our sadistic viewing pleasure. In Mars One, the contestants are expected to die on set, which is a fate arguably even worse than having Simon Cowell touch you (more contestants will be sent out every two years, with the aim of establishing a self-sustaining community, but there will be no trips home).</p><p></p><p>Yet there still seems something heroic about this silly project. The Earth will be burned to a crisp and swallowed up by a bloated red-giant Sun in about 7bn years. If we haven't got used to colonising other planets and eventually other star systems by then, that will be the end of the human race.</p><p></p><p>If governments are no longer willing to fund such inspirational <em>grands projets</em>, we should be happy that other entities think they can raise the money instead, even if those entities are TV producers (the idea of privatised game-show space tourism would surely have tickled Lady Thatcher). And for those who think interplanetary exploration is just nonsense for space nerds, the same lessons could surely be applied closer to home.</p><p></p><p>Let's have a reality-TV contest in which top materials-science researchers vie to invent a more efficient kind of solar cell in order to combat global warming, while also having to rehearse and perform an entire postmodern circus in skimpy costumes. Or, since 61% of the UK public now believe that utilities are better run in public hands, we could make a reality-TV show out of economists and other wonks trying desperately to renationalise the electricity supply. I for one am quite optimistic about the viewing figures for Britain's Got Current.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/netherlands\">Netherlands</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/nasa\">Nasa</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/europe-news\">Europe</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/space\">Space</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/mars\">Mars</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/reality-tv\">Reality TV</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/stevenpoole\">Steven Poole</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Netherlands") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/science")) "Nasa") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Europe") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/science")) "Space") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/science")) "Science") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/science")) "Mars") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Reality TV") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Comment") (pubDate nil "Fri, 19 Apr 2013 16:35:37 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/19/reality-tv-mars-landing") (dc:creator nil "Steven Poole") (dc:subject nil "Comment is free") (dc:date nil "2013-04-19T16:35:37Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407519014") (media:keywords nil "Netherlands, Nasa, Europe, World news, Space, Science, Mars, Reality TV, Television") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/19/1366379693114/Mars-in-space-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AP") (media:description nil "'In Mars One, the contestants are expected to die on set, which is a fate arguably even worse than having Simon Cowell touch you.' Photograph: AP")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/19/1366379698569/Mars-in-space-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "AP") (media:description nil "'In Mars One, the contestants are expected to die on set, which is a fate arguably even worse than having Simon Cowell touch you.' Photograph: AP")))) ("Have comedy panel shows had their day?" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/68710?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Asweat-the-small-stuff-comedy-panel-shows%3A1896474&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=GU.co.uk&c4=Comedy+%28TV+genre%29%2CCulture%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CComedy%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Rhik+Samadder&c7=2013%2F04%2F19+06%3A28&c8=1896474&c9=Blog&c10=Blogpost&c13=&c19=GUK&c25=TV+and+radio+blog+%28television%29&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Sweat+the+Small+Stuff%3A+have+comedy+panel+shows+had+their+day%3F&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FComedy\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Cheap, formulaic, blokey banter is near impossible to miss on primetime weekend TV. Good luck to Nick Grimshaw and his new BBC3 panel show in reviving a very, very tired format ...</p><p><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ytSHcE4fx6Q\" title=\"\">Comedy panel shows have been around since 700BC</a>. They are popular, cheap and have filled a huge chunk of primetime  previously given over to ... well, no one can remember what came before, but ... anyway. They're not without their critics, who point out the fact that they simply employ the same 10 men (and one woman) over and over again in schedule-swamping ubiquity.</p><p>Surely television needs another panel-show like Noah needed a paper hat. So good news! BBC Three have announced Sweat the Small Stuff (\"share little things that drive you crazy\"), a comedy panel show hosted by Radio 1 and Kiss FM DJs Nick Grimshaw, Rickie Haywood-Williams and Melvin O'Doome (and Rochelle from the Saturdays). </p><p>So can Rick, Mel and Grimmy carve any worthwhile niche in the wall of chatter? Their breakfast radio manner is jocular but gentle. They are young, urban, trendy (meaning two of them are black, Grimshaw is gay, and they're all under 40). They're charming, likeable and pretty funny, in the way that strangers on the bus can sometimes be funny. But is that enough?</p><p>While good chemistry has always been a vital component amongst presenters, \"top banter\" is now the lingua franca of primetime, making conversations between cricketers and comedians and pop stars palatable to a studio audience. It is louder than chemistry, competitive and crass. There is an entire channel devoted to it, yet proven banter kings roam carnivorously over other channels, singly, or in dyads and triads, like Bantersaurus Rex.</p><p>It's not that it's not fun. The pleasure of banter is the simulacrum of friendship. Playfighting says \"the bonds between us are robust, though we may only ever meet in green rooms over complimentary cashew nuts\". It's a clubbable, blokey, sexually normative way of cracking unwise. Which is all fine, in a balanced diet. But the endlessly repeated flatpack format of the comedy panel means a television break is increasingly less viable (or desirable) for other sorts of funny. Shows such as 8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown indicate that men teasing each other may soon become the only way we know how to watch anything, even televisual sudoku. Not convinced? Let's have a look at a few of \"the classics\" currently gracing our screens.</p><h2>Have I Got News For You</h2><p>Venerated elder of the form. Indisputably funny, at least in the days before it was discovered that erstwhile host Angus Deayton did not like to relax in ways that were legal. Pushes on into dotage, though it seems Paul Merton has stopped noticing or caring.</p><h2>Mock the Week</h2><p>Much loved – is love the right word? Much … <em>watched</em> satirical news quiz. Has become a byword for the bearpit mentality of similar shows. Boasts an extremely high gag-rate, as does standing in front of a tennis-ball cannon loaded with cracker gags and sperm. Sample burn: \"Susan Boyle looks like Gordon Brown doing Mrs Doubtfire.\"</p><h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hrMCj4avEks\" title=\"\">8 Out of 10 Cats</a></h2><p>Those who like being offended by Jimmy Carr but have trouble following his peripatetic hosting schedule can always find him here. Carr, like other reliable, over-employed guests such as Sean Lock, Rhod Gilbert and Russell Howard inhabit multiple positions simultaneously on the panel show spectrum, like Schrödinger's prats.</p><h2>QI</h2><p>After the successful crusade of alternative comedy, time was when cries of \"Oxbridge smuggery\" would reverberate around its crenellations. Now QI, under the tutelage of National Trust property Stephen Fry, is universally hailed as a respite from the populist mush surrounding it. Sample Fry pun: \"People cling to fallacies for years. I've clung to fallacies.\" (NB. this donnish zinger doesn't work so well on paper, it being homophonic.)</p><h2>A League of Their Own</h2><p>\"Ebullient\" \"personalities\" Jack Whitehall and James Corden chuck swearwords and bat eyelashes at each other on Sky1. Of course we need sports comedy shows because professional sportspeople are notorious wits. If you've ever wondered how banter between the changing room and the pub sounds, you are partly responsible for this mess.</p><h2><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=h7nKCeDz7LU\" title=\"\">Celebrity Juice</a></h2><p>Has female team captains – hurrah! Unfortunately anchored by monotonous boor Keith Lemon (Avid Merrion). An unwatchable charnel house.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/rhik-samadder\">Rhik Samadder</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-