app which offers the quickest, easiest way to arrange sexual hook-ups? If Grindr really is an example of gay culture then is dogging an example of \"straight culture\"? And if not, why not?</p><p>Britain's lesbian and gay community has made massive strides in recent years. We have an equal age of consent, employment rights and a whole raft of legal protections we didn't have a decade ago. Soon the UK will even follow in the footsteps of countries like Spain and South Africa and grant same sex couples the right to marry.</p><p>So where does that leave gay culture? For many people, gay culture begins and ends with the gay scene. There are gay magazines devoted to it, and gay people who devote their lives to it. And compared to many countries, we have a gay scene we can be proud of. But all is not well in this rosy pink world. The impact of <a href=\"http://www.gaystarnews.com/article/drug-epidemic-hitting-gay-men-hard010412\" title=\"\">drugs like GHB</a> has led to numerous deaths on the London gay scene. Next month, the Royal Vauxhall Tavern in the capital is hosting a panel discussion to address the problem. The fact that it's presented by someone called Sleazy Michael gives some idea of the target audience.</p><p>Of course, gay culture isn't confined to the scene. There's also the mainstream. Take television. A decade ago, people said that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2003/sep/15/channel4.gayrights\" title=\"\">Queer As Folk </a>had changed everything. But creator Russell T Davies was the first to admit that it hadn't. As wonderful as Queer As Folk was, it didn't change the way gay men are routinely portrayed on TV. We still have the familiar line-up of camp comedians we've had since the 1970s. The names have changed, but the mannerisms haven't. Once, gay men were associated with the wit and wisdom of Oscar Wilde. Now it's the huff and puff of – well, take your pick.</p><p>Coming up soon on ITV we have the much publicised sitcom Vicious, starring gay national treasures <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2012/nov/05/ian-mckellen-derek-jacobi-vicious\" title=\"\">Ian McKellen and Derek Jacobi</a>. The original title was Vicious Old Queens. Nothing wrong with that, of course. Such people exist. But this story could have been told 40 years ago – and was, with <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Staircase_%28film%29\" title=\"\">Richard Burton and Rex Harrison</a> as an older, squabbling gay couple in the film Staircase.</p><p>We've climbed a long way up the social ladder since Staircase was first shown in 1969. From this vantage point, it's easier to see things from a wider perspective. And with greater legislative freedoms, we have an opportunity to take a broader view of gay politics, and redefine what we mean by gay culture.</p><p>It was with this in mind that Guardian writer Julie Bindel and I decided to launch a new online magazine called <a href=\"http://www.gaze-amodernreview.co.uk/\" title=\"\">Gaze – A Modern Review</a>. We didn't want to write about gay lifestyle or pander to straight soap hunks who love their gay fans. We wanted to tackle issues one doesn't generally read about in the lesbian and gay press. For too long, gay people were defined by the expectations of heterosexuals – and we ended up in a ghetto, with a narrow view of the world beyond. Now the legal battles are mostly won, isn't it time we reclaimed all of culture – not just the \"gay\" bits – for ourselves?</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/gay-rights\">Gay rights</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/sexuality\">Sexuality</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/apps\">Apps</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/paul-burston\">Paul Burston</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "Gay rights") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Sexuality") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/world")) "World news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology")) "Apps") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology")) "Technology") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Comment") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 09:30:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2013/apr/20/gay-culture-grindr-scene") (dc:creator nil "Paul Burston") (dc:subject nil "Comment is free") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T09:30:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407526031") (media:keywords nil "Gay rights, Sexuality, World news, Apps, Technology, Media, Television, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/19/1366385529525/Gay-pride--003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Andy Hall/Andy Hall") (media:description nil "Mardi Gras and gay pride in Finsbury Park, London. Photograph: Andy Hall")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2013/4/19/1366385535677/Gay-pride--008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Andy Hall/Andy Hall") (media:description nil "Mardi Gras gay pride in Finsbury Park, London. 'For too long, gay people were defined by the expectations of heterosexuals and we ended up in a ghetto.' Photograph: Andy Hall")))) ("TV review: The Ice Cream Girls" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/42698?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Athe-ice-cream-girls-review%3A1896680&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Culture%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Sam+Wollaston&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+08%3A00&c8=1896680&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Last+nights+TV+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=TV+review%3A+The+Ice+Cream+Girls&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FDrama\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">On ITV, flashbacks can be triggered by almost anything, finds Sam Wollaston</p><p>There's a nagging little bell going off in my head during the first of three episodes of <strong>The Ice Cream Girls</strong> (ITV), adapted from <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2001/sep/01/weekend7.weekend7\" title=\"\">Dorothy Koomson</a>'s novel. And it's getting louder. Someone leaves prison; there's the whiff of a miscarriage of justice; a family moves to the seaside, by Volvo, for a fresh start; then FLASHBACK! – bad shit happened in the past; now it's time for it to catch up ...</p><p>Got it! <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2012/dec/10/tv-review-the-poison-tree\" title=\"\">The Poison Tree</a>, adapted from the novel by Erin Kelly, just a few months ago on the same channel. They love the old prison-Volvo-to-the-coast-flashback-novel psychological-thriller adaptation at ITV. That's not to say there's not plenty of intrigue here. Serena (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/15/lorraine-burroughs-favourite-tv\" title=\"\">Lorraine Borroughs</a>) returns to her childhood town with her new family, to a dying mother and to terrible memories. Of a rape, a murder, and another girl, Poppy (Jodhi May), who was convicted of murder – of a teacher who abused them both – but may not have done it.</p><p>But (and it shares this with The Poison Tree, too), there's an obviousness to it. An ITV drama-ness about it. It's so consciously trying to be a psychological thriller, not just your bog-standard thriller. Brows are knitted to mournful cellos, Poppy shouts from a motorway bridge, and there's a lot of staring out to sea, which inevitably brings on further&nbsp;flashbacks.</p><p>These are triggered by almost anything: photos, newspaper cuttings, the beach hut, a particular street. At one point Serena, driving in the Volvo with her husband, even overtakes her younger self. Maybe they should have given her a lift. \"Hop in, love – oh, I'm you, by the way, in the future. I&nbsp;wouldn't go in there, incidentally, it's trouble.\" I also thought Evan, the husband, was a bit too cheerful and unbothered about moving in with his sick mother-in-law. What kind of man are you? A small thing, I know.</p><p>I'll watch the rest, because it's enthralling enough for me to want to know what happens, or rather what happened 17 years ago. But I won't be lying awake at night thinking about it.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/samwollaston\">Sam Wollaston</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/the-ice-cream-girls-review" (20850 15644) old 22 nil nil ((title nil "TV review: The Ice Cream Girls") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/the-ice-cream-girls-review") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/42698?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Athe-ice-cream-girls-review%3A1896680&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Culture%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Sam+Wollaston&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+08%3A00&c8=1896680&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Last+nights+TV+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=TV+review%3A+The+Ice+Cream+Girls&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FDrama\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">On ITV, flashbacks can be triggered by almost anything, finds Sam Wollaston</p><p>There's a nagging little bell going off in my head during the first of three episodes of <strong>The Ice Cream Girls</strong> (ITV), adapted from <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2001/sep/01/weekend7.weekend7\" title=\"\">Dorothy Koomson</a>'s novel. And it's getting louder. Someone leaves prison; there's the whiff of a miscarriage of justice; a family moves to the seaside, by Volvo, for a fresh start; then FLASHBACK! – bad shit happened in the past; now it's time for it to catch up ...</p><p>Got it! <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2012/dec/10/tv-review-the-poison-tree\" title=\"\">The Poison Tree</a>, adapted from the novel by Erin Kelly, just a few months ago on the same channel. They love the old prison-Volvo-to-the-coast-flashback-novel psychological-thriller adaptation at ITV. That's not to say there's not plenty of intrigue here. Serena (<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/15/lorraine-burroughs-favourite-tv\" title=\"\">Lorraine Borroughs</a>) returns to her childhood town with her new family, to a dying mother and to terrible memories. Of a rape, a murder, and another girl, Poppy (Jodhi May), who was convicted of murder – of a teacher who abused them both – but may not have done it.</p><p>But (and it shares this with The Poison Tree, too), there's an obviousness to it. An ITV drama-ness about it. It's so consciously trying to be a psychological thriller, not just your bog-standard thriller. Brows are knitted to mournful cellos, Poppy shouts from a motorway bridge, and there's a lot of staring out to sea, which inevitably brings on further&nbsp;flashbacks.</p><p>These are triggered by almost anything: photos, newspaper cuttings, the beach hut, a particular street. At one point Serena, driving in the Volvo with her husband, even overtakes her younger self. Maybe they should have given her a lift. \"Hop in, love – oh, I'm you, by the way, in the future. I&nbsp;wouldn't go in there, incidentally, it's trouble.\" I also thought Evan, the husband, was a bit too cheerful and unbothered about moving in with his sick mother-in-law. What kind of man are you? A small thing, I know.</p><p>I'll watch the rest, because it's enthralling enough for me to want to know what happens, or rather what happened 17 years ago. But I won't be lying awake at night thinking about it.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/samwollaston\">Sam Wollaston</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 07:00:44 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/the-ice-cream-girls-review") (dc:creator nil "Sam Wollaston") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T07:00:45Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407533467"))) ("Julia Sawalha's kitchen nightmare" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/21728?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ajulia-sawalha-kitchen-nightmare%3A1896096&ch=Money&c3=Guardian&c4=Home+improvements%2CConsumer+affairs+%28Money%29%2CConsumer+rights+%28Money%29%2CProperty+%28Money+-+UK+consumer%29%2CMoney%2CHomes+%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CCulture&c5=Personal+Finance%2CHomes+and+Gardens%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CProperty+Mortgages+and+Interest+Rates%2CTelevision+Media%2CConsumer+News&c6=Rupert+Jones&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A59&c8=1896096&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Julia+Sawalha%27s+kitchen+nightmare&c66=Money&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FMoney%2FMoney%2FHome+improvements\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">As Saffy in Ab Fab, Julia Sawalha despaired in her mother's kitchen. In real life, buying her own upmarket kitchen became a personal drama</p><p>In her role as strait-laced Saffy in long-running sitcom Absolutely Fabulous, Julia Sawalha spent a great deal of time in one of the most famous kitchens on British television, with its champagne-filled fridge and little-used oven. But the actor is now embroiled in a real-life kitchen drama.</p><p>Sawalha told Guardian Money she faced losing up to £15,000 after she decided to cancel an order for a new kitchen for the property she is restoring when the company upped the price after the deal was agreed.</p><p>She told us she was being \"excessively penalised\" after the firm refused to refund her £10,000 deposit then demanded she pay a further £5,000 to buy herself out of the contract. Sawalha claims the \"appalling\" way she was treated had left her in tears.</p><p>Luxury kitchen maker Chalon – whose designs regularly feature in upmarket property and interiors magazines – claimed that Sawalha had been \"unreasonable\" but told us it was \"close to reaching an amicable agreement\". There was talk of a refund of the bulk of the £10,000, but as Money went to press, Sawalha told us this had not materialised, despite a deadline having been set.</p><p>Sawalha, who is also well-known for her roles in BBC period dramas Lark Rise to Candleford, Cranford and Pride and Prejudice, is restoring her \"dream home\", a Grade I listed townhouse in Bath, which she spent years saving up for. She decided to treat herself to a Chalon kitchen, which are well-known for their \"distressed\" paint finishes: \"I've been salivating over their adverts in magazines for years.\"</p><p>Although Sawalha was planning to fork out a lot more than the average £8,000, she is far from alone in having a run-in with a kitchen firm. Which? says that around 40% of its members have experienced problems.</p><p>A friend alerted her to Money's consumer champions, who take up reader complaints without naming the individuals. We asked if she was willing to go on the record and she agreed. She told us that in January she visited Chalon's showroom in London's King's Road and was told she could have someone visit her home and draw up a design free of charge.</p><p>She says she made clear that she didn't want a kitchen \"island\" and preferred built-in units to separate pieces, because the latter would be too big for the room. However, she says that when she returned to the showroom, she was presented with a design for a \"separate piece\" kitchen, which included an island, with a total price-tag of £47,400.</p><p>Sawalha says she again made clear she didn't want separate pieces, and the designer agreed to change the design to a \"modular\" kitchen, bringing the cost down to £37,400. Based on this, she handed over a cheque for £10,000 on 4 February. Next day she decided she didn't want the island or the wall cupboard above it, and the designer agreed to remove them. With these two items valued at a total of £9,480, she assumed this would take the cost down to £27,900.</p><p>Sawalha says that for two weeks she heard nothing, and with her electrician \"champing at the bit,\" had to chase the firm. It eventually sent her a new quote which appears to omit the island and cupboard, but is for £39,700 – more than the originally agreed amount, she says. Oddly, this quote states that the deposit amount is £13,115.</p><p>Sawalha asked how the quote could be higher after the two pieces had been removed, and said she was \"becoming more and more confused and, quite frankly, stressed with the way things are progressing\". Next day she received an email apologising for the \"confusion\". It stated that \"we can bring the kitchen to around £37,000\", and that Sawalha would be sent \"a revised quote and plan\" following the engineer's visit.</p><p>\"I was shocked to learn there would be a revised quote, and alarm bells started to ring,\" she says. \"As far as I'm concerned, a company doesn't sell a product at a certain price then increase the price once the deal has been agreed. I thought: where will they draw the line?\"</p><p>On 22 February she emailed Chalon to say that as she could not seem to get any clear answers, she didn't wish to go ahead and wanted her deposit refunded. However, the company declined. On 2 March, it did offer her the kitchen she wanted for £27,900, from which her deposit would be deducted, plus a free piece of furniture \"as a thank you for your patience\", but Sawalha says: \"By this point I was extremely stressed and did not trust them at all, and the thought of having to look at their kitchen for the next 20 years after all the upset they had caused was simply not an option.\"</p><p>But that wasn't the end of the matter. This month Chalon emailed Sawalha's solicitor to say that it \"would look for £15,000 in compensation to include its administrative costs and loss of profit\" – ie, she would have to pay an extra £5,000 to escape the contract.</p><p>The actor says: \"My solicitors have told them no losses have been incurred. The designer's service was free of charge, no engineer visited the property and the kitchen never went into production. To be so excessively penalised for changing my mind… I can't understand how I can be charged £10,000-£15,000 for a product that hasn't even been made.\"</p><p>She adds that she was not given a contract to sign. However, the company told her in an email that a legal contract had been made, adding: \"In your case, you gave the deposit over rather than signed a contract.\"</p><p>Sawalha says of the saga: \"It's put a huge cloud over my whole restoration project and is holding things up massively. I feel utterly depressed every time I walk into the kitchen. At the end of the day there are a lot worse things going on in the world, but at the same time it's a huge amount of stress I could do without.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/homeimprovements\">Home improvements</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/consumer-affairs\">Consumer affairs</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/consumer-rights-money\">Consumer rights</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/property\">Property</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/homes\">Homes</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/rupertjones\">Rupert Jones</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2013/apr/20/julia-sawalha-kitchen-nightmare" (20850 11944) old 23 nil nil ((title nil "Julia Sawalha's kitchen nightmare") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2013/apr/20/julia-sawalha-kitchen-nightmare") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/21728?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ajulia-sawalha-kitchen-nightmare%3A1896096&ch=Money&c3=Guardian&c4=Home+improvements%2CConsumer+affairs+%28Money%29%2CConsumer+rights+%28Money%29%2CProperty+%28Money+-+UK+consumer%29%2CMoney%2CHomes+%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CCulture&c5=Personal+Finance%2CHomes+and+Gardens%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CProperty+Mortgages+and+Interest+Rates%2CTelevision+Media%2CConsumer+News&c6=Rupert+Jones&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A59&c8=1896096&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Julia+Sawalha%27s+kitchen+nightmare&c66=Money&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FMoney