mount of stress I could do without.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/homeimprovements\">Home improvements</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/consumer-affairs\">Consumer affairs</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/consumer-rights-money\">Consumer rights</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/property\">Property</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/homes\">Homes</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/rupertjones\">Rupert Jones</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money")) "Home improvements") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money")) "Consumer affairs") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money")) "Consumer rights") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money")) "Property") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money")) "Money") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Homes") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Life and style") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 05:59:04 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/money/2013/apr/20/julia-sawalha-kitchen-nightmare") (dc:creator nil "Rupert Jones") (dc:subject nil "Money") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T05:59:04Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407458609") (media:keywords nil "Home improvements, Consumer affairs, Consumer rights, Property, Money, Homes, Life and style, Television, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/MONEY/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366372540554/julia-sawalha-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "SWNS.com") (media:description nil "Ab Fab's Julia Sawalha feels 'utterly depressed every time I walk into the kitchen' after dispute with Chalon. Photograph: SWNS.com")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/MONEY/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366372550764/julia-sawalha-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "SWNS.com") (media:description nil "Ab Fab's Julia Sawalha feels 'utterly depressed every time I walk into the kitchen' after dispute with Chalon. Photograph: SWNS.com")))) ("Radio review: from Unknown Cities to Ode To Finchleystrasse" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/14399?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Adavid-hepworth-radio-review%3A1895439&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Radio+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media&c6=David+Hepworth&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A00&c8=1895439&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=David+Hepworth+on+radio+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Radio+review%3A+from+Unknown+Cities+to+Ode+To+Finchleystrasse&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FRadio\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Unknown Cities | Coronation Strasse | Ode To Finchleystrasse</p><p>TV travel shows venture only as far as they can persuade a celebrity presenter to go. Even then they have to be certain that they'll come back with some pretty pictures. Which explains why they don't do much that's as interesting as <strong>Unknown Cities</strong>, this week's variation on Radio 3's The Essay strand (<em>weeknights, 10.45am R3</em>).</p><p>Here, four exceptional voices describe faraway places of which we know nothing. Well, nothing at the moment, though we may have done in the past and we may do in the future. Nicholas Shakespeare does Hobart in Tasmania, which once supplied the whale oil that kept Victorian London illuminated and was described as \"the cesspit of the Empire\". Romesh Gunesekera describes Kunming in China and its \"surprisingly genuine roadside massage parlours, in which you're pummelled by blind masseurs\". Michela Wrong speaks of Asmara, the Eritrean city that still bears the marks of Mussolini's attempts to turn it into the Milan of the Horn of Africa. Best of all is Vanora Bennett's story about Makhachkala, the city in Dagestan with such a worrying reputation that its Wikitravel page practically leads with the legend \"Don't go there – please\". Even the multimillionaire footballers such as Samuel Eto'o Fils who play in its colours are flown in for the games, returning to their Moscow fastness as soon as the final whistle has gone. Bennett went there to write a book about caviar smuggling, which has made some of the locals so rich they live in an area of the city known as \"Santa Barbara\".</p><p>As power tilts ever eastwards, these cities may become as fixed in our imaginations as Chicago and Paris once were. These 15-minute portraits, expertly paced and beautifully delivered, will set the tone. In time, when each town has its own branch of McDonald's, it's possible the TV people may fly their celebrities there and put pictures to those words.</p><p>I suspect it's the name that got <strong>Coronation Strasse </strong>(<em>Saturday, 10.30am R4</em>) commissioned. Although Germany's long-running soap Lindenstraße was originally inspired by the Weatherfield drama, it doesn't seem to have much in common, though I enjoyed the leading actor's laconic recap of her character's CV: \"I've been playing Tanya for 26 years. When I was 15 I became a tennis star. I fell in love with the lover of my mother, my mother killed herself, my father drunk himself to death, my sister died of cancer, then I got into being an escort girl. I got saved by a guy who's 30 years older and was in a wheelchair, then I got a lesbian lover who tried to kill my husband, who then killed my lesbian lover. Then I found a new love and I got a child with another woman, who left me for another man, and now I live alone with my child. I'm a hairdresser.\"</p><p><strong>Ode To Finchleystrasse </strong>(<em>Wednesday, 11am R4</em>) is the latest in the Journeys Down My Street series, about the UK's long-established immigrant communities. It's covered Poles in Bradford, Somalis in Cardiff, and now the German and Austrian Jews who fled Hitler in the 1930s and ended up living around the famed north London artery within easy reach of the now-late Cosmo Cafe. The title comes from the recollection of one Austrian Jew that the bus conductors would announce their arrival at Finchley Road thusly. The programme-makers are so tickled with their title that they overplay their hand, asking another elderly interviewee whether she can remember it being called that. \"No,\" she says.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/davidhepworth\">David Hepworth</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/david-hepworth-radio-review" (20850 8411) old 24 nil nil ((title nil "Radio review: from Unknown Cities to Ode To Finchleystrasse") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/david-hepworth-radio-review") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/14399?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Adavid-hepworth-radio-review%3A1895439&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Radio+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media&c6=David+Hepworth&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A00&c8=1895439&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=David+Hepworth+on+radio+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Radio+review%3A+from+Unknown+Cities+to+Ode+To+Finchleystrasse&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FRadio\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Unknown Cities | Coronation Strasse | Ode To Finchleystrasse</p><p>TV travel shows venture only as far as they can persuade a celebrity presenter to go. Even then they have to be certain that they'll come back with some pretty pictures. Which explains why they don't do much that's as interesting as <strong>Unknown Cities</strong>, this week's variation on Radio 3's The Essay strand (<em>weeknights, 10.45am R3</em>).</p><p>Here, four exceptional voices describe faraway places of which we know nothing. Well, nothing at the moment, though we may have done in the past and we may do in the future. Nicholas Shakespeare does Hobart in Tasmania, which once supplied the whale oil that kept Victorian London illuminated and was described as \"the cesspit of the Empire\". Romesh Gunesekera describes Kunming in China and its \"surprisingly genuine roadside massage