ser.\"</p><p><strong>Ode To Finchleystrasse </strong>(<em>Wednesday, 11am R4</em>) is the latest in the Journeys Down My Street series, about the UK's long-established immigrant communities. It's covered Poles in Bradford, Somalis in Cardiff, and now the German and Austrian Jews who fled Hitler in the 1930s and ended up living around the famed north London artery within easy reach of the now-late Cosmo Cafe. The title comes from the recollection of one Austrian Jew that the bus conductors would announce their arrival at Finchley Road thusly. The programme-makers are so tickled with their title that they overplay their hand, asking another elderly interviewee whether she can remember it being called that. \"No,\" she says.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/davidhepworth\">David Hepworth</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 05:00:11 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/david-hepworth-radio-review") (dc:creator nil "David Hepworth") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T05:00:11Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407386637") (media:keywords nil "Radio, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366214780525/Vanora-Bennett-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "HarperCollins") (media:description nil "Vanora Bennett. Photograph: HarperCollins")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366214786153/Vanora-Bennett-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "HarperCollins") (media:description nil "Vanora Bennett. Photograph: HarperCollins")))) ("Catch-up TV guide: from Adventure Time to All Songs Considered" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/81822?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Acatch-up-tv-guide%3A1895406&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Gwilym+Mumford+%28contributor%29&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A00&c8=1895406&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=TV+and+radio+catch+up+guide&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Catch-up+TV+guide%3A+from+Adventure+Time+to+All+Songs+Considered&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Adventure Time | Tribeca Film Festival Experience | Broadchurch | The Century That Wrote Itself | Boss | All Songs Considered</p><h2>TV: Adventure Time</h2><p>Heated debates rage online as to which is the best kids' show of the moment: Pendleton Ward's wildly inventive animation or the no-less frenetic Regular Show. For us, Adventure Time just nicks it, largely due to its superior voice cast: Mark Hamill, Henry Rollins and Emo Philips are some of the names to have provided voices for the show's bizarre cast of characters. Non-Cartoon Network viewers can catch up with the first four series on iTunes.</p><p><a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/gb/tv-season/adventure-time-vol.-1/id437023463\" title=\"\"><em>iTunes</em></a></p><h2>Film: Tribeca Film Festival Experience</h2><p>Cineastes unable to attend New York's Tribeca film festival can find some consolation in the form of this pay-per-view sextet of official selection titles, which include the Rashida Jones-starring break-up drama Monogamy; and Rubberneck, a psychological thriller directed by and starring Alex Karpovsky (Girls' laconic man-child Ray). Available until June.</p><p><em>Virgin Media, iTunes, Xbox Live, PlayStation</em></p><h2>TV: Broadchurch</h2><p>So, after eight weeks of drip-fed tension, we finally find out who offed Danny Latimer this Monday at 9pm, as ITV's ratings smash concludes. Those who have failed to keep pace, meanwhile, can fidget nervously through the final quintet of episodes over on the ITV Player.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.itv.com/itvplayer/broadchurch\" title=\"\"><em>ITV Player</em></a></p><h2>TV: The Century That Wrote Itself</h2><p>Adam Nicolson presents this examination of the evolution of writing in the 1600s, a century in which, he robustly argues, we set off down \"the track to modernity\", as figures outside the nobility began to pick up pen and paper. The final episode airs 9pm on Wednesday, while the series in full is on the iPlayer until 1 May.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01rvzts/The_Century_that_Wrote_Itself_The_Written_Self/\" title=\"\">BBC iPlayer</a></p><h2>TV: Boss</h2><p>Replacing the bumptious amiability of Frasier Crane with an unblinking, feral intensity, Kelsey Grammer remains a watchable presence in this political drama (airing on 11pm, Thursdays, More4) as his Chicago mayor, Tom Kane, continues in his quest to tear up a rotten political scene before a degenerative neurological disorder claims him. Find out how he gets on over on 4oD.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/boss/4od\" title=\"\"><em>4oD</em></a></p><h2>Radio: All Songs Considered</h2><p>The Flaming Lips' inimitable frontman Wayne Coyne played the role of DJ for a special edition of NPR's music show recently, sharing tunes from the Lips' gonzo new album The Terror as well as the Beatles, Beach House and – in typically off-piste fashion – Tom Jones's theme from Thunderball. Catch up with the episode, as well as a full archive of past instalments over on NPR's website.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.npr.org/blogs/allsongs/\" title=\"\"><em>npr.org</em></a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/gwilym-mumford\">Gwilym Mumford</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/catch-up-tv-guide" (20850 8408) old 25 nil nil ((title nil "Catch-up TV guide: from Adventure Time to All Songs Considered") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/catch-up-tv-guide") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/81822?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Acatch-up-tv-guide%3A1895406&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Gwilym+Mumford+%28contributor%29&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A00&c8=1895406&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=TV+and+radio+catch+up+guide&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Catch-up+TV+guide%3A+from+Adventure+Time+to+All+Songs+Considered&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Adventure Time | Tribeca Film Festival Experience | Broadchurch | The Century That Wrote Itself | Boss | All Songs Considered</p><h2>TV: Adventure Time</h2><p>Heated debates rage online as to which is the best kids' show of the moment: Pendleton Ward's wildly inventive animation or the no-less frenetic Regular Show. For us, Adventure Time just nicks it, largely due to its superior voice cast: Mark Hamill, Henry Rollins and Emo Philips are some of the names to have provided voices for the show's bizarre cast of characters. Non-Cartoon Network viewers can catch up with the first four series on iTunes.</p><p><a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/gb/tv-season/adventure-time-vol.-1/id437023463\" title=\"\"><em>iTunes</em></a></p><h2>Film: Tribeca Film Festival Experience</h2><p>Cineastes unable to attend New York's Tribeca film festival can find some consolation in the form of this pay-per-view sextet of official selection titles, which include the Rashida Jones-starring break-up drama Monogamy; and Rubberneck, a psychological thriller directed by and starring Alex Karpovsky (Girls' laconic man-child Ray). Available until June.</p><p><em>Virgin Media, iTunes, Xbox Live, PlayStation</em></p><h2>TV: Broadchurch</h2><p>So, after eight weeks of drip-fed tension, we finally find out who offed Danny Latimer this Monday at 9pm, as ITV's ratings smash concludes. Those who have failed to keep pace, meanwhile, can fidget nervously through the final quintet of episodes over on the ITV Player.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.itv.com/itvplayer/broadchurch\" title=\"\"><em>ITV Player</em></a></p><h2>TV: The Century That Wrote Itself</h2><p>Adam Nicolson presents this examination of the evolution of writing in the 1600s, a century in which, he robustly argues, we set off down \"the track to modernity\", as figures outside the nobility began to pick up pen and paper. The final episode airs 9pm on Wednesday, while the series in full is on the iPlayer until 1 May.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01rvzts/The_Century_that_Wrote_Itself_The_Written_Self/\" title=\"\">BBC iPlayer</a></p><h2>TV: Boss</h2><p>Replacing the bumptious amiability of Frasier Crane with an unblinking, feral intensity, Kelsey Grammer remains a watchable presence in this political drama (airing on 11pm, Thursdays, More4) as his Chicago mayor, Tom Kane, continues in his quest to tear up a rotten political scene before a degenerative neurological disorder claims him. Find out how he gets on over on 4oD.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/boss/4od\" title=\"\"><em>4oD</em></a></p><h2>Radio: All Songs Considered</h2><p>The Flaming Lips' inimitable frontman Wayne Coyne played the role of DJ for a special edition of NPR's music show recently, sharing tunes from the Lips' gonzo new album The Terror as well as the Beatles, Beach House and – in typically off-piste fashion – Tom Jones's theme from Thunderball. Catch up with the episode, as well as a full archive of past instalments over on NPR's website.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.npr.org/blogs/allsongs/\" title=\"\"><em>npr.org</em></a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/gwilym-mumford\">Gwilym Mumford</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 05:00:08 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/catch-up-tv-guide") (dc:creator nil "Gwilym Mumford") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T05:00:08Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407383473") (media:keywords nil "Television, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366212521217/Adventure-Time-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Adventure Time")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366212527761/Adventure-Time-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Adventure Time")))) ("The new Santander advert: making sport creepy" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/59775?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Athe-new-santander-advert%3A1895422&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Advertising+%28media%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+industry+%28Media%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CMedia%2CCulture%2CRory+McIlroy+%28sport%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CAdvertising+Media%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Sian+Rowe&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A00&c8=1895422&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=The+hard+sell+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+new+Santander+advert%3A+making+sport+creepy&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FAdvertising\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">'He looks so lost and awkward, yet so blankly creepy, that you may want to simultaneously cuddle him and bludgeon him with one of his own clubs'</p><p><br /><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/01JkaMPUR4A?enablejsapi=1&version=3\">Reading this on mobile? Click here to view</a></p><p>Every successful sportsperson needs a hobby. Footballers buy racehorses (Wayne Rooney) or go carp fishing (John Terry). Some tennis players own fashion brands (Venus Williams). In their downtime sportspeople also appear in adverts. And look! Here's scarlet-faced golf pixie Rory McIlroy infiltrating homes across the country to update you about the latest banking deals. \"With a 123 current account, you can get 1% cashback on your water bills,\" he says, sinisterly appearing in the bathroom mirror like the seed of Chucky with a country club membership. He stares. There's an awkward pause. He pats a man's face with a towel. He stares again.</p><p>Jenson Button is in it, too – advert super-fans may remember him rhyming \"racing\", \"spacing\" and \"bracing\" to demonstrate just how good anti-dandruff shampoo was in 2011 – as is Jessica Ennis. But really this belongs to the permanently polo-shirted ball hitter. Next he's in the home of an artist. He reaches into her fruit bowl. He picks up an apple. He says something about interest. He bites the apple. He looks so lost and awkward, yet so blankly creepy, that you may want to simultaneously cuddle him and bludgeon him with one of his own clubs just to make it end. There's only one positive to take from it, and it isn't financial advice. When a fan recently tweeted @McIlroyRory that he was \"a terrible actor\", he showed a very un-celeb-like level of self-awareness. It was very refreshing. \"I have to agree!!\" he replied. \"No oscars coming my way anytime soon!\" Oscar? Let's hope Santander takes pity, and never makes him act again.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/advertising\">Advertising</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/television\">Television industry</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/rory-mcilroy\">Rory McIlroy</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/the-new-santander-advert" (20850 8400) old 26 nil nil ((title nil "The new Santander advert: making sport creepy") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/the-new-santander-advert") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/59775?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Athe-new-santander-advert%3A1895422&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Advertising+%28media%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+industry+%28Media%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CMedia%2CCulture%2CRory+McIlroy+%28sport%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CAdvertising+Media%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Sian+Rowe&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A00&c8=1895422&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=The+hard+sell+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=The+new+Santander+advert%3A+making+sport+creepy&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FAdvertising\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">'He looks so