ardian.co.uk/media/advertising\">Advertising</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/television\">Television industry</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/rory-mcilroy\">Rory McIlroy</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Advertising") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Television industry") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport")) "Rory McIlroy") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Guardian") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 05:00:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/the-new-santander-advert") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T05:00:09Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407385508") (media:keywords nil "Advertising, Television, Television industry, Television & radio, Media, Culture, Rory McIlroy") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366213769295/Rory-McIlroy-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "He's behind you … Rory McIlroy")))) ("America In Primetime, an engrossing squint at US television" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/8519?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aamerica-in-primetime-engrossing-doc%3A1895343&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture%2CUS+television+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CDocumentary+%28TV+genre%29%2CFactual+TV+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Sarah+Dempster&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A00&c8=1895343&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=TV+OD+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=America+In+Primetime%2C+an+engrossing+squint+at+US+television&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">• Sarah Dempster's TV OD: From Dick Van Dyke to Tony Soprano, America In Primetime tries to find the definitive US TV dad</p><p>Who is the definitive American TV dad? What are his hopes and fears? How does he deal with change? Where did he get that hat? Are those Findus Crispy Pancakes? Why is he shouting at us to get off his porch? Ooh, is that a gun? These and other vexed questions are addressed in the first episode of <strong>America In Primetime</strong> (<em>Saturday, 10.15pm, BBC2</em>), a wholly engrossing four-part stare through the net curtains of US TV. It's a weighty 2011 PBS series gently Britished-up by the BBC, with tonight's opener taking a thorough squint at the history of that most familiar and conflicted of fictional small-screen idols: the primetime patriarch. An introductory \"representative domestic incidents\" montage invites us to feel the width of the bugger's MO. Dick Van Dyke skipping through his front door in a trilby; Homer Simpson telling daughter Lisa that, hey, just because he doesn't <em>care</em> doesn't mean he doesn't <em>understand</em>; Tony Soprano burying his face in a metaphor for modern masculinity that's also a plate of linguine. Here, says America In Primetime, is a figure that encapsulates 60 years of American TV maleness, from the sexless omniscience of the postwar breadwinner to the achy-breaky self-doubt of today's Mr Boo Hoos.</p><p>\"He just wishes he could get a little bit of peace and quiet once in a while,\" says Carl Reiner of this perturbed cultural touchstone. \"He is looking for meaning and not finding it,\" says Sopranos creator David Chase. \"It isn't always easy to glean the true nature of homo domesticus,\" warns presenter Alan Yentob, turning up in a shirt the colour of conjunctivitis. But never mind him. Apparently, what it all boils down to is balls. Fifties dad had a heart and a briefcase but \"no balls\". But then, \"Finally!\" bellows a pundit of The Cosby Show's unyielding Cliff Huxtable, \"a dad that had SOME BALLS.\"</p><p>The balls continue to bounce through an absorbing roundup of modern TV neuroses: from the conflicted clock-weights of the cable-drama antihero to the flattened testicular pucks of the perennially abused sitcom schlub. Eventually, we arrive at the gulping, tremulous creature first seen in wildly influential baby-boomer blubathon Thirtysomething: his masculinity as over-thought as his designer beard; his scrotum little more than a sliver of (organic, locally sourced) luncheon meat flapping in the postmodern, post-second-wave-feminism breeze. Not that feminism gets much of a look-in here. In fact, female characters and the impact of women's changing roles on homo domesticus are barely mentioned at all (although there are numerous corking talking-head contributions from the likes of Roseanne Barr and Diablo Cody). This is a strictly chaps-only club. The clips do sit-ups and the anecdotes wear Paco Rabanne, and yet this ploy works brilliantly. What could have been an empty 21-gun trouser salute to the majestic preeminence of man is instead a thoughtful, concentrated study of the primetime patriarch as a discrete and ever-evolving entity. (Besides which, a later episode is devoted entirely to the depiction of small-screen ladies. So, y'know, woo hoo.)</p><p>We end with a look at Mad Men's Don Draper and Breaking Bad's Walter White: two sides of the same misery coin and the perfect demonstration of Ron Howard's assertion that \"TV is becoming literature\". So to the inevitable grumble: where are the British small-screen heroes? God knows there's nothing duller than the endless \"they're-better-no-we're-better-oh-why-can't-we-all-be-friends\" UK vs US TV \"debate\" but sod it: where are our believable patriarchs? Our Walter Whites? Our long-running, life-changing dramas in which devastating, excoriating self-examination doesn't mean someone blowing his nose in Holby City, or the unbearable lightness of being Stephen Tompkinson? If America In Primetime knows, it isn't telling. Waiter! A wheelbarrow for this series' balls.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/us-television\">US television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/documentary\">Documentary</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/factual-tv\">Factual TV</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/sarahdempster\">Sarah Dempster</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/america-in-primetime-engrossing-doc" (20850 8400) old 2 nil nil ((title nil "America In Primetime, an engrossing squint at US television") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/america-in-primetime-engrossing-doc") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/8519?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aamerica-in-primetime-engrossing-doc%3A1895343&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Guardian&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture%2CUS+television+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CDocumentary+%28TV+genre%29%2CFactual+TV+%28TV+genre%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media%2CTV&c6=Sarah+Dempster&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+06%3A00&c8=1895343&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=TV+OD+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=America+In+Primetime%2C+an+engrossing+squint+at+US+television&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">• Sarah Dempster's TV OD: From Dick Van Dyke to Tony Soprano, America In Primetime tries to find the definitive US TV dad</p><p>Who is the definitive American TV dad? What are his hopes and fears? How does he deal with change? Where did he get that hat? Are those Findus Crispy Pancakes? Why is he shouting at us to get off his porch? Ooh, is that a gun? These and other vexed questions are addressed in the first episode of <strong>America In Primetime</strong> (<em>Saturday, 10.15pm, BBC2</em>), a wholly engrossing four-part stare through the net curtains of US TV. It's a weighty 2011 PBS series gently Britished-up by the BBC, with tonight's opener taking a thorough squint at the history of that most familiar and conflicted of fictional small-screen idols: the primetime patriarch. An introductory \"representative domestic incidents\" montage invites us to feel the width of the bugger's MO. Dick Van Dyke skipping through his front door in a trilby; Homer Simpson telling daug