/a> a government-funded strategy launched last year and credited with generating £300m in additional tourism spending.</p><p>\"The coup of landing Wallace & Gromit for the campaign's second push is great news,\" said the tourism minister, Hugh Robertson. \"Their ad will no doubt capture the imagination, encourage people to have a fresh look at what England as a holiday destination has to offer and boost domestic tourism further.\"</p><p>And if anywhere needs a boost it is Blackpool, thought to have the highest level of youth unemployment in the north-west of England. The numbers of residents claiming jobseeker's allowance may have decreased from 6,226 in January to 6,179 in February, but there are thousands of young people hoping to get seasonal work at its tourist attractions this summer.</p><p>The town also faces a threat to its image as a safe place to sunbathe and swim, or ride a donkey, as it waits to hear whether the water quality of the sea is about to earn it a bathing ban.</p><p>Two years ago another of the town's traditional attractions, the illuminations along its lengthy promenade, were also tarnished by accusations from Blackpool businesses that the council were was scrimping on bulbs and had failed to repair storm damage</p><p>For Thompson, Park's decision to put his faith in Blackpool is crucial. \"We are very proud of the ride and we know that families will want to ride it again and again to see all their favourite characters,\" she said.</p><p>Later this summer 1.5-metre (5ft) tall Gromits will appear on the streets of Bristol – where Aardman is based. Gromit Unleashed exhibition runs for 10 weeks from July, after which the sculptures, which have been designed and created by invited artists, will be auctioned to raise funds for the Bristol Children's Hospital Charity.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/blackpool\">Blackpool</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/wallace-and-gromit\">Wallace and Gromit</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/aardman\">Aardman</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/animation\">Animation</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/film/animation\">Animation</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/vanessathorpe\">Vanessa Thorpe</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "Blackpool") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Wallace and Gromit") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Aardman") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Animation") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Animation") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/film")) "Film") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "guardian.co.uk") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "News") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 11:06:54 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2013/apr/21/wallace-gromit-blackpool-grand-day-out") (dc:creator nil "Vanessa Thorpe") (dc:subject nil "UK news") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T11:46:01Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407586778") (media:keywords nil "Blackpool, Wallace and Gromit, Aardman, Animation, Animation, Film, Television, UK news") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/21/1366542374589/Wallace-and-Gromits-Thril-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Wallace and Gromit's Thrill-O-Matic ride at Blackpool Pleasure Beach, which takes passengers seated in a giant slipper through key scenes from the duo's films.")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/21/1366542383102/Wallace-and-Gromits-Thril-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "Wallace and Gromit's Thrill-O-Matic ride at Blackpool Pleasure Beach, which takes passengers seated in a giant slipper through key scenes from the duo's films.")))) ("Marian Keyes: 'I thought I'd never be able to write again'" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/52148?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amarian-keyes-depression-mercy-close-interview%3A1894757&ch=Books&c3=Obs&c4=Marian+Keyes+%28Books%29%2CDepression+%28Society%29%2CChick+lit+%28Books+genre%29%2CMental+health+%28Society%29%2CCome+Dine+With+Me%2CPrada+%28Fashion%29%2CBooks%2CCulture%2CFiction+%28Books+genre%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CHealth+Society%2CTV&c6=Elizabeth+Day&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+09%3A00&c8=1894757&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CInterview&c13=The+New+Review+Q+and+A+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Marian+Keyes%3A+%27I+thought+I%27d+never+be+able+to+write+again%27&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FBooks%2FMarian+Keyes\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The Irish novelist talks about her crippling depression, the power of Come Dine with Me, and why she can't wait to be 50 – or 70</p><p><strong>You wrote your latest book, <em>The Mystery of Mercy Close</em>, in the grip of what you have previously described as a nervous breakdown. Does it feel miraculous that it got written at all?</strong></p><p>It does. I'm amazed. I really, really thought I'd never be able to write again. I had long months of catatonic, unable-to-get-out-of-bedness and then long months of this incredible fear, in the grip of panic. So the book was written very peculiarly. There was no steadiness to it. It took much longer than anything else I've written … I veered off into making cakes for about a year. I was wondering quite seriously: \"Could baking be my job?\" And I'm still not 100% so anything I managed to produce is a miracle.</p><p></p><p><strong>It must have been terrifying to feel like&nbsp;that...</strong></p><p>I've always been prone to depression, and I've been very public about my alcoholism even though I haven't had a drink in 19 years. I thought because I was addressing my issues on a daily basis I wouldn't be one of those people who suddenly blew, but I did. I can still feel the fear. It was very primal. It wasn't anxiety – I was terrified and everything looked different. It felt like I'd landed on another planet and it was horrific. I was just so frightened all the time. But all I was diagnosed with was depression and anxiety. I'm not bipolar, I'm not schizophrenic, but obviously something did shift in my head.</p><p></p><p><strong>There's a point in the book where your no-nonsense heroine Helen Walsh has just been diagnosed with depression and has trouble taking it in because she thinks: \"There was no such thing as depression… Muffins, that was the cure.\" Did you struggle with acceptance of it?</strong></p><p>In a way yes. I've always been melancholic. At a party, everyone would be looking at the glittering chandeliers and I'd be looking at the waitress's cracked shoes. But the catatonia, the being unable to sleep … it was a shock to me that actually, this was far worse.</p><p></p><p><strong>There's also a scene where Helen buys a Stanley knife and makes an elaborate plan to slit her wrists in a hotel room, leaving a note of apology in English and Polish for the chambermaid who might find her body. Did you do that?</strong></p><p>I did. Twice. I had two goes going out assembling the whole kit and buying paper and Sellotape to write the note. The conversation Helen has with the man in the shop, I actually had that, with him asking: \"What is it you're proposing to cut?\" It was so bizarre to be standing in a DIY shop, buying a knife to open my veins with. I was absolutely going through who would find me, leaving money for her to apologise… I wasn't in my right mind.</p><p></p><p><strong>I read somewhere that you knew something was wrong when you started finding the sight of Prada handbags frightening...</strong></p><p>It was dreadful! I was at the airport – I'd been on holiday but had to come home early, and I was in Duty Free. Normally I'd be breaking my neck to get in there. But there is something in Miuccia Prada's vision that is slightly sinister isn't there?</p><p></p><p><strong>Have you got over that?</strong></p><p>I have – more's the pity really! I had a great spell of buying absolutely nothing. I lived in the same three pairs of jeans for a year.</p><p></p><p><strong>Is it true that <em>Come Dine With Me </em>got you through some of your lowest points?</strong></p><p>Oh. My. God. Literally not joking, it saved my life. I loved your Dave Lamb [the narrator]. It's so very, very involving. It's about human beings, it's fun and it's short. I was at the stage when I was counting the minutes to get through a certain time so <em>Come Dine With Me </em>was great because I could watch it and be half an hour closer to sunset. Even now, at sunset, something lifts off me. That's how it is. Some days are better than others.</p><p></p><p><strong>So how are you today?</strong></p><p>I'm uneasy, which is huge progress. I'm not looking for pity, I'm really not, but I'm constantly uneasy and every day it is pretty much like getting up and going to war. Once I shift into the mindset of \"Yeah, you're alive. It's tough. Let's do what we can today,\" it's easier. The big mistake I made was thinking that happiness is the default position. Whereas it's just one of the countless states of mind we endure. I've kind of realised life is meant to be tough and everybody is in psychic and spiritual discomfort of some sort and has a burden to carry. I've realised I'm not special.</p><p></p><p><strong>But you're renowned as a funny writer. Is it difficult to write humour when you're in this state of mind?</strong></p><p>At the risk of sounding like a big boasty boaster, to be funny is easier for me than anything else. I feel very lucky because I think it's genetic. My mother has this way of structuring sentences that is extremely, uproariously funny. I think, also, coming from Ireland – it's a huge cliche but I think we have a different vocabulary and we structure our sentences according to the rhythms of the old language we used to speak. It's more colourful and more entertaining. And then, of course, I suppose Irish people do put so much value on anecdote. It's almost a competitive sport.</p><p></p><p><strong>Although your novels are often tagged as chick lit, they tackle serious issues. In the past, you've written about domestic violence, drug addiction and bereavement. Are there any topics you wouldn't take on?</strong></p><p>Never say never. I used to think I would never write about domestic violence because I didn't want to do it wrong, I didn't want to do a disservice to the women who had been through it. Then I was just so interested in it, in how rife it is and how secretive and ashamed the women are who have been through it, that I did it anyway. I've covered nearly everything.</p><p></p><p><strong>You describe yourself as a feminist. Do you think publishing is a sexist industry?</strong></p><p>This is hard, now, to answer. I don't know if it's sexist but it's just so genderised. The way much of women's fiction is marketed and packaged, it could be called sexist. But then I suppose crime writers might also feel marginalised. I think it's inevitable that publishers who are essentially purveyors are going to package the product in a way that reaches an optimal marketplace. I think reviewers are sexist… This isn't to sound bitter but I think you're more likely to get a critical kicking if you're a woman. I just think that's a fact. I really think less value is put in general on women's voices, across the&nbsp;board.</p><p></p><p><strong>You turn 50 later this year. Are you having a party?</strong></p><p>I'm not. Christ alive, I'd rather fling myself into the canal. Being the centre of attention – it's a vision of hell for me. I'm going to go to Pizza Express down the road. I have no fear of turning 50 whatsoever. I love getting older. I've always felt the world expects less of me as I get older so I'm free to be more and more eccentric. I've no regrets. Jesus, I wouldn't have my 20s back for all the money in the universe... I can't wait to be 70.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/marian-keyes\">Marian Keyes</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/depression\">Depression</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/chick-lit\">Chick lit</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/mental-health\">Mental health</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/come-dine-with-me\">Come Dine With Me</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/fashion/prada\">Prada</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/fiction\">Fiction</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/elizabethday\">Elizabeth Day</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/21/marian-keyes-depression-mercy-close-interview" (20851 40081) old 13 nil nil ((title nil "Marian Keyes: 'I thought I'd never be able to write again'") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/21/marian-keyes-depression-mercy-close-interview") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/52148?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Amarian-keyes-depression-mercy-close-interview%3A1894757&ch=Books&c3=Obs&c4=Marian+Keyes+%28Books%29%2CDepression+%28Society%29%2CChick+lit+%28Books+genre%29%2CMental+health+%28Society%29%2CCome+Dine+With+Me%2CPrada+%28Fashion%29%2CBooks%2CCulture%2CFiction+%28Books+genre%29&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CHealth+Society%2CTV&c6=Elizabeth+Day&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+09%3A00&c8=1894757&c9=Article&c10=Feature%2CInterview&c13=The+New+Review+Q+and+A+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Marian+Keyes%3A+%27I+thought+I%27d+never+be+able+to+write+again%27&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FBooks%2FMarian+Keyes\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The Irish novelist talks about her crippling depression, the power of Come Dine with Me, and why she can't wait to be 50 – or 70</p><p><strong>You wrote your latest book, <em>The Mystery of Mercy Close</em>, in the grip of what you have previously described as a nervous breakdown. Does it feel miraculous that it got written at all?</strong></p><p>It does. I'm amazed. I really, really thought I'd never be able to write again. I had long months of catatonic, unable-to-get-out-of-bedness and then long months of this incredible fear, in the grip of panic. So the book was written very peculiarly. There was no steadiness to it. It took much longer than anything else I've written … I veered off into making cakes for about a year. I was wondering quite seriously: \"Could baking be my job?\" And I'm still not 100% so anything I managed to produce is a miracle.</p><p></p><p><strong>It must have been terrifying to feel like&nbsp;that...</strong></p><p>I've always been prone to depression, and I've been very public about my alcoholism even though I haven't had a drink in 19 years. I thought because I was addressing my issues on a daily basis I wouldn't be one of those people who suddenly blew, but I did. I can still feel the fear. It was very primal. It wasn't anxiety – I was terrified and everything looked different. It felt like I'd landed on another planet and it was horrific. I was just so frightened all the time. But all I was diagnosed with was depression and anxiety. I'm not bipolar, I'm not schizophrenic, but obviously something did shift in my head.</p><p></p><p><strong>There's a point in the book where your no-nonsense heroine Helen Walsh has just been diagnosed with depression and has trouble taking it in because she thinks: \"There was no such thing as depression… Muffins, that was the cure.\" Did you struggle with acceptance of it?</strong></p><p>In a way yes. I've always been melancholic. At a party, everyone would be looking at the glittering chandeliers and I'd be looking at the waitress's cracked shoes. But the catatonia, the being unable to sleep … it was a shock to me that actually, this was far worse.</p><p></p><p><strong>There's also a scene where Helen buys a Stanley knife and makes an elaborate plan to slit her wrists in a hotel room, leaving a note of apology in English and Polish for the chambermaid who might find her body. Did you do that?</strong></p><p>I did. Twice. I had two goes going out assembling the whole kit and buying paper and Sellotape to write the note. The conversation Helen has with the man in the shop, I actually had that, with him asking: \"What is it you're proposing to cut?\" It was so bizarre to be standing in a DIY shop, buying a knife to open my veins with. I was absolutely going through who would find me, leaving money for her to apologise… I wasn't in my right mind.</p><p></p><p><strong>I read somewhere that you knew something was wrong when you started finding the sight of Prada handbags frightening...</strong></p><p>It was dreadful! I was at the airport – I'd been on holiday but had to come home early, and I was in Duty Free. Normally I'd be breaking my neck to get in there. But there is something in Miuccia Prada's vision that is slightly sinister isn't there?</p><p></p><p><strong>Have you got over that?</strong></p><p>I have – more's the pity really! I had a great spell of buying absolutely nothing. I lived in the same three pairs of jeans for a year.</p><p></p><p><strong>Is it true that <em>Come Dine With Me </em>got you through some of your lowest points?</strong></p><p>Oh. My. God. Literally not joking, it saved my life. I loved your Dave Lamb [the narrator]. It's so very, very involving. It's about human beings, it's fun and it's short. I was at the stage when I was counting the minutes to get through a certain time so <em>Come Dine With Me </em>was great because I could watch it and be half an hour closer to sunset. Even now, at sunset, something lifts off me. That's how it is. Some days are better than others.</p><p></p><p><strong>So how are you today?</strong></p><p>I'm uneasy, which is huge progress. I'm not looking for pity, I'm really not, but I'm constantly uneasy and every day it is pretty much like getting up and going to war. Once I shift into the mindset of \"Yeah, you're alive. It's tough. Let's do what we can today,\" it's easier. The big mistake I made was thinking that happiness is the default position. Whereas it's just one of the countless states of mind we endure. I've kind of realised life is meant to be tough and everybody is in psychic and spiritual discomfort of some sort and has a burden to carry. I've realised I'm not special.</p><p></p><p><strong>But you're renowned as a funny writer. Is it difficult to write humour when you're in this state of mind?</strong></p><p>At the risk of sounding like a big boasty boaster, to be funny is easier for me than anything else. I feel very lucky because I think it's genetic. My mother has this way of structuring sentences that is extremely, uproariously funny. I think, also, coming from Ireland – it's a huge cliche but I think we have a different vocabulary and we structure our sentences according to the rhythms of the old language we used to speak. It's more colourful and more entertaining. And then, of course, I suppose Irish people do put so much value on anecdote. It's almost a competitive sport.</p><p></p><p><strong>Although your novels are often tagged as chick lit, they tackle serious issues. In the past, you've written about domestic violence, drug addiction and bereavement. Are there any topics you wouldn't take on?</strong></p><p>Never say never. I used to think I would never write about domestic violence because I didn't want to do it wrong, I didn't want to do a disservice to the women who had been through it. Then I was just so interested in it, in how rife it is and how secretive and ashamed the women are who have been through it, that I did it anyway. I've covered nearly everything.</p><p></p><p><strong>You describe yourself as a feminist. Do you think publishing is a sexist industry?</strong></p><p>This is hard, now, to answer. I don't know if it's sexist but it's just so genderised. The way much of women's fiction is marketed and packaged, it could be called sexist. But then I suppose crime writers might also feel marginalised. I think it's inevitable that publishers who are essentially purveyors are going to package the product in a way that reaches an optimal marketplace. I think reviewers are sexist… This isn't to sound bitter but I think you're more likely to get a critical kicking if you're a woman. I just think that's a fact. I really think less value is put in general on women's voices, across the&nbsp;board.</p><p></p><p><strong>You turn 50 later this year. Are you having a party?</strong></p><p>I'm not. Christ alive, I'd rather fling myself into the canal. Being the centre of attention – it's a vision of hell for me. I'm going to go to Pizza Express down the road. I have no fear of turning 50 whatsoever. I love getting older. I've always felt the world expects less of me as I get older so I'm free to be more and more eccentric. I've no regrets. Jesus, I wouldn't have my 20s back for all the money in the universe... I can't wait to be 70.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/marian-keyes\">Marian Keyes</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/depression\">Depression</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/chick-lit\">Chick lit</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/mental-health\">Mental health</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/come-dine-with-me\">Come Dine With Me</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/fashion/prada\">Prada</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/fiction\">Fiction</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/elizabethday\">Elizabeth Day</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Marian Keyes") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Depression") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Chick lit") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Mental health") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Come Dine With Me") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/fashion")) "Prada") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Books") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books")) "Fiction") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Observer") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Interviews") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 08:00:17 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2013/apr/21/marian-keyes-depression-mercy-close-interview") (dc:creator nil "Elizabeth Day") (dc:subject nil "Books") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T08:00:17Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407300198") (media:keywords nil "Marian Keyes, Depression, Chick lit, Mental health, Come Dine With Me, Prada, Books, Culture, Fiction") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Columnist/Columnists/2013/4/16/1366125405379/marian-keyes-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Felix Clay/Guardian") (media:description nil "Marian Keyes: 'To be funny is easier for me than anything else.' Photograph: Felix Clay for the Guardian")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Columnist/Columnists/2013/4/16/1366125412680/marian-keyes-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Felix Clay/Guardian") (media:description nil "Marian Keyes: 'To be funny is easier for me than anything else.' Photograph: Felix Clay for the Guardian")))) ("Chloe Madeley and her mother Judy Finnigan on their special relationship" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/66194?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Achloe-madeley-mother-judy-finnigan%3A1895049&ch=Media&c3=Obs&c4=Judy+Finnigan%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CMedia%2CRelationships+%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CTelevision+Media%2CFamily+and+Relationships&c6=Katie+Burnetts&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+06%3A59&c8=1895049&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=Me+and+you+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Chloe+Madeley+and+her+mother+Judy+Finnigan+on+their+special+relationship&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FMedia%2FJudy+Finnigan\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Chloe Madeley and Judy Finnigan on the perils of working in TV, being emotional, and supporting each other no matter what</p><h2>Her story <em>Chloe Madeley</em>, 25, presenter</h2><p></p><p>Mum and Dad started <a href=\"http://www.itv.com/thismorning/\" title=\"\"><em>This Morning</em></a><em> </em>the year I was born, so I was aware from a young age that they were famous. People would come up to us at Sunday lunch and say how much they liked the show. It made me very proud that people knew who they were, but there was a darker side. By age five I knew what to do if someone \"doorstepped\" us or if I saw someone rifling through our bins.</p><p>A lot of the time I had a nanny. But I never felt like I&nbsp;didn't come first. Mum always made time to be a mother. On weekends she would sit down next to me, hold my hand or sit me on her lap and make me talk about my week. She would continuously try to get to know me. One of my earliest memories is of her desperately trying to construct my hair into one of those buns for ballet. I was four and only had about five strands. She was crying and getting emotional about it, and I remember saying: \"Don't worry, Mum.\"</p><p>We're both very emotional and suffer with anxiety. I've had a weird few years – I got a lot of flak from the press, and I'm not the kind of person who can take it. Whenever I'm having a hard time, Mum guides me through. She understands how a situation can become overwhelming. When she first started at <em>This Morning</em>, she would sit in the toilet having an anxiety attack before she went on air.</p><p>Mum is withdrawn and very shy. I don't see her as a&nbsp;friend, like I do my dad. He's active and bouncy. She's maternal, nurturing, exceptionally intelligent and empathetic. I'm a&nbsp;better person for having had her as a&nbsp;mother. She's at her happiest when all our family is there – and when she's happy, everything that comes out of her mouth is comic genius. The&nbsp;thing is, I don't think she realises how funny she is.</p><p></p><p><br /></p><h2>Her story <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/judy-finnigan\" title=\"\">Judy Finnigan</a>, 64, author and broadcaster</h2><p></p><p>In our family <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chloe_Madeley\" title=\"\">Chloe</a> is the baby, and the only girl. She has two brothers, 10 years older, who have spoiled her and always found her funny. We're similar in that we both cry a lot. In other ways I don't think we're similar at all. She's more outgoing and sociable – she gets that from Richard. He's gregarious and can talk to anyone about anything.</p><p>Something that's always struck me about Chloe is how physically fearless she is. She used to climb up the insides of door frames in the house. When she was three, we went to a water park in Portugal. I put her in a swimming costume, put her armbands on, turned around for one second and she'd vanished. We were all panic-stricken, shouting: \"Chloe! Where are you?!\" Then she came hurtling down the biggest water slide in the park wearing the biggest smile.</p><p>When Chloe did Dancing on Ice she'd never skated before. We went along every week and I had to cover my eyes. I was terrified about the lifts, but she doesn't have one frightened bone in her body.</p><p>We've always talked about everything, and I don't feel Chloe's ever kept anything from us. I'm not a&nbsp;disciplinarian, though sometimes I think I should have been. I had quite a&nbsp;strict upbringing, so I've gone the opposite way.</p><p>I get cross when Chloe's restless. She's impulsive and can suddenly decide that she's going to drive to Essex late at night to see her boyfriend. That sort of thing irritates me, but we don't tend to argue. Chloe's freelance right now, so she hasn't got a regular income, but when she's ready to move out I'll help her. I will miss her like mad.</p><p></p><p><br />Judy Finnigan's debut novel, <a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9780751548600\" title=\"\">Eloise</a>, is out now and published by Sphere</p><p></p><p><br />If you'd like to appear in this column, email <a href=\"http://meandyou@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\">meandyou@observer.co.uk</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/judy-finnigan\">Judy Finnigan</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/relationships\">Relationships</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2013/apr/21/chloe-madeley-mother-judy-finnigan" (20851 32807) old 14 nil nil ((title nil "Chloe Madeley and her mother Judy Finnigan on their special relationship") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2013/apr/21/chloe-madeley-mother-judy-finnigan") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/66194?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Achloe-madeley-mother-judy-finnigan%3A1895049&ch=Media&c3=Obs&c4=Judy+Finnigan%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CMedia%2CRelationships+%28Life+and+style%29%2CLife+and+style&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CMedia+Weekly%2CTelevision+Media%2CFamily+and+Relationships&c6=Katie+Burnetts&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+06%3A59&c8=1895049&c9=Article&c10=Feature&c13=Me+and+you+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Chloe+Madeley+and+her+mother+Judy+Finnigan+on+their+special+relationship&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FMedia%2FJudy+Finnigan\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Chloe Madeley and Judy Finnigan on the perils of working in TV, being emotional, and supporting each other no matter what</p><h2>Her story <em>Chloe Madeley</em>, 25, presenter</h2><p></p><p>Mum and Dad started <a href=\"http://www.itv.com/thismorning/\" title=\"\"><em>This Morning</em></a><em> </em>the year I was born, so I was aware from a young age that they were famous. People would come up to us at Sunday lunch and say how much they liked the show. It made me very proud that people knew who they were, but there was a darker side. By age five I knew what to do if someone \"doorstepped\" us or if I saw someone rifling through our bins.</p><p>A lot of the time I had a nanny. But I never felt like I&nbsp;didn't come first. Mum always made time to be a mother. On weekends she would sit down next to me, hold my hand or sit me on her lap and make me talk about my week. She would continuously try to get to know me. One of my earliest memories is of her desperately trying to construct my hair into one of those buns for ballet. I was four and only had about five strands. She was crying and getting emotional about it, and I remember saying: \"Don't worry, Mum.\"</p><p>We're both very emotional and suffer with anxiety. I've had a weird few years – I got a lot of flak from the press, and I'm not the kind of person who can take it. Whenever I'm having a hard time, Mum guides me through. She understands how a situation can become overwhelming. When she first started at <em>This Morning</em>, she would sit in the toilet having an anxiety attack before she went on air.</p><p>Mum is withdrawn and very shy. I don't see her as a&nbsp;friend, like I do my dad. He's active and bouncy. She's maternal, nurturing, exceptionally intelligent and empathetic. I'm a&nbsp;better person for having had her as a&nbsp;mother. She's at her happiest when all our family is there – and when she's happy, everything that comes out of her mouth is comic genius. The&nbsp;thing is, I don't think she realises how funny she is.</p><p></p><p><br /></p><h2>Her story <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/judy-finnigan\" title=\"\">Judy Finnigan</a>, 64, author and broadcaster</h2><p></p><p>In our family <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chloe_Madeley\" title=\"\">Chloe</a> is the baby, and the only girl. She has two brothers, 10 years older, who have spoiled her and always found her funny. We're similar in that we both cry a lot. In other ways I don't think we're similar at all. She's more outgoing and sociable – she gets that from Richard. He's gregarious and can talk to anyone about anything.</p><p>Something that's always struck me about Chloe is how physically fearless she is. She used to climb up the insides of door frames in the house. When she was three, we went to a water park in Portugal. I put her in a swimming costume, put her armbands on, turned around for one second and she'd vanished. We were all panic-stricken, shouting: \"Chloe! Where are you?!\" Then she came hurtling down the biggest water slide in the park wearing the biggest smile.</p><p>When Chloe did Dancing on Ice she'd never skated before. We went along every week and I had to cover my eyes. I was terrified about the lifts, but she doesn't have one frightened bone in her body.</p><p>We've always talked about everything, and I don't feel Chloe's ever kept anything from us. I'm not a&nbsp;disciplinarian, though sometimes I think I should have been. I had quite a&nbsp;strict upbringing, so I've gone the opposite way.</p><p>I get cross when Chloe's restless. She's impulsive and can suddenly decide that she's going to drive to Essex late at night to see her boyfriend. That sort of thing irritates me, but we don't tend to argue. Chloe's freelance right now, so she hasn't got a regular income, but when she's ready to move out I'll help her. I will miss her like mad.</p><p></p><p><br />Judy Finnigan's debut novel, <a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9780751548600\" title=\"\">Eloise</a>, is out now and published by Sphere</p><p></p><p><br />If you'd like to appear in this column, email <a href=\"http://meandyou@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\">meandyou@observer.co.uk</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/judy-finnigan\">Judy Finnigan</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/relationships\">Relationships</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Judy Finnigan") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Media") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Relationships") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Life and style") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Observer") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Features") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 05:59:03 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2013/apr/21/chloe-madeley-mother-judy-finnigan") (dc:creator nil) (dc:subject nil "Media") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T05:59:03Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407348183") (media:keywords nil "Judy Finnigan, Television, Television & radio, Media, Relationships, Life and style") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366192837974/Judy-Finnigan-with-daught-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "'A lot of the time I had a nanny. But I never felt like I didn't come first. Mum always made time to be a mother': Chloe Madeley on her mother Judy Finnigan.")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/4/17/1366192844426/Judy-Finnigan-with-daught-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "PR") (media:description nil "'I had a nanny. But I never felt like I didn't come first. Mum always made time to be a mother': Chloe Madeley, seen here as a baby with her mother Judy Finnigan")))) ("Casualty was right to take on female genital mutilation" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/35008?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Acasualty-was-right-female-genital-mutilation%3A1895094&ch=Society&c3=Obs&c4=Female+genital+mutilation+%28FGM%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CHealth+and+wellbeing+%28Life+and+style%29%2CHealth+%28Society%29%2CWomen+and+women%27s+interests%2CSociety&c5=Society+Weekly%2CUnclassified%2CWomen%2CHealth+Society%2CHealth%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Eva+Wiseman&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+06%3A30&c8=1895094&c9=Article&c10=Comment&c13=The+Eva+Wiseman+column+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Casualty+was+right+to+take+on+female+genital+mutilation&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FSociety%2FFemale+genital+mutilation+%28FGM%29\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">In an agenda-setting episode, Casualty featured a storyline that squared up to one of the most culturally sensitive issues in Britain – female genital mutilation</p><p>BBC's <em>Casualty</em> is not a&nbsp;programme known for its light touch. It doesn't tiptoe around issues – it bashes down their door and runs through them with boots on. In <em>Casualty</em>, cars are leather-seated smash-smash machines. In <em>Casualty</em>, windows are brittle mouths of doom. If I were mayor of the fictional town of Holby I&nbsp;would pedestrianise the hell out of it. I'd compress every tower block into a bungalow and enforce compulsory parachutes for everyone with cause to climb a ladder. But <em>Casualty</em>'s lack of subtlety, its very black-and-whiteness, is why it was exactly the right forum to&nbsp;address <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/female-genital-mutilation\" title=\"\">female genital mutilation</a> for the first time in British drama.</p><p>This is what happened <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2013/apr/12/casualty-spotlight-female-genital-mutilation\" title=\"\">on BBC1 at 9.10pm on Saturday, </a>with 5 million people watching. Tamasha wanted to protect her little sister from being cut like her. The doctors were debating whether to get involved: \"It's too culturally sensitive,\" argued one. \"It's complex.\" \"Typical liberal excuse,\" replied the nurse. Meanwhile the sisters' pregnant mother was going into early labour, and upon inspecting her, Dr Hanna learned she was \"closed\". In one of those great flashes of <em>Casualty</em> karma, when Tamasha caught up with the private doctor on his way to the cutting party and ran him off the road in her mother's car, he suffered massive trauma to his genitals. Dr Hanna and Tamasha drove to a terraced house, where, in the absence of the private doctor, two little girls had been cut by their grandmother – one lay unconscious in a pool of blood and urine.</p><p>There were some concerns online before it aired, commenters saying the BBC shouldn't show the story because it would be upsetting viewing, and it was – it was upsetting. But this isn't the time for <em>Newsnight</em> or <em>Panorama</em>. This is the time for family TV, for faces we recognise, for blood and broad strokes of script. There's little room for subtlety any more. Not when we're talking about the removal of more than 66,000 women's clitorises in the UK alone, with 20,000 more (16,000 of whom are under 15) at risk. About the cutting of their labia, sometimes the sewing up of their vaginas, leaving only a tiny opening for blood and urine.</p><p>It's partly because of this – the language required to talk about it – that discussion about FGM remains in the serious bits of the paper, only alluded to on grown-up television and debated in Parliament. It's partly because of this, and partly because it's seen as a&nbsp;potentially incendiary problem, with teachers and doctors reluctant to intervene for fear of appearing racist or interfering in traditions they don't quite understand.</p><p>Germaine Greer once argued that attempts to outlaw genital mutilation amounted to \"an attack on cultural identity\", and she wasn't alone. Over time, advocates for cultural self-determination have quieted slightly as human rights arguments have been clarified, but there's still the worry. That by calling social services when you suspect that your student's summer holiday (for this is when it often happens) will involve her being held down by six women while her genitals are cut, you will come across as insensitive. Yet if there was the real threat of a child being blinded, say, or a limb amputated, you would react at speed.</p><p>Despite it being illegal to perform FGM here, and to take children out  of the country to have it performed, there has never been a single conviction. The lack of arrests says terrible things about our ignorance, our apathy and, crucially, our ideas about female sexuality.</p><p>So yeah, the time for subtlety has passed. The law isn't working – traumatised children are not calling the police on their mothers, who believe they're doing the best for their daughters. Girls are still being cut. This is the time for noisy statements on prime-time TV. This is what drama is for. And <em>Casualty</em>, with its bright lights and clanking scripts, has timed its action just right. Because it's getting warmer.&nbsp;The summer holidays are close.</p><h2>On the Web</h2><p>Email Eva at <a href=\"mailto:e.wiseman@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\">e.wiseman@observer.co.uk</a> or visit <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/evawiseman\" title=\"\">guardian.co.uk/profile/evawiseman</a> for all her articles in one place. Follow Eva on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EvaWiseman\" title=\"\">Twitter@EvaWiseman</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/female-genital-mutilation\">Female genital mutilation (FGM)</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/health-and-wellbeing\">Health & wellbeing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/health\">Health</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/women\">Women</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/evawiseman\">Eva Wiseman</a></div><br/