<p>Email Eva at <a href=\"mailto:e.wiseman@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\">e.wiseman@observer.co.uk</a> or visit <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/evawiseman\" title=\"\">guardian.co.uk/profile/evawiseman</a> for all her articles in one place. Follow Eva on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/EvaWiseman\" title=\"\">Twitter@EvaWiseman</a></p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/female-genital-mutilation\">Female genital mutilation (FGM)</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/health-and-wellbeing\">Health & wellbeing</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/health\">Health</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/women\">Women</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/evawiseman\">Eva Wiseman</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Female genital mutilation (FGM)") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Health & wellbeing") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Health") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle")) "Women") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society")) "Society") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Observer") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Comment") (pubDate nil "Sun, 21 Apr 2013 05:30:00 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2013/apr/21/casualty-was-right-female-genital-mutilation") (dc:creator nil "Eva Wiseman") (dc:subject nil "Society") (dc:date nil "2013-04-21T08:33:37Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407353014") (media:keywords nil "Female genital mutilation (FGM), Television, Health & wellbeing, Health, Women, Society") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366398724784/Casualty-003.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Adrian Rogers/BBC") (media:description nil "\"This isn't the time for Newsnight or Panorama. There's little room for subtlety any more. Not when we're talking about the removal of more than 66,000 women's clitorises in the UK alone.\"  Photograph: Adrian Rogers/BBC")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/4/19/1366398732283/Casualty-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Adrian Rogers/BBC") (media:description nil "\"This isn't the time for Newsnight or Panorama. There's little room for subtlety any more. Not when we're talking about the removal of more than 66,000 women's clitorises in the UK alone.\"  Photograph: Adrian Rogers/BBC")))) ("Rewind radio: Jon Ronson On… Being Normal; The Funeral of Baroness Thatcher; Jeremy Vine – review" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/35393?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ajon-ronson-on-being-normal-review%3A1895877&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Obs&c4=Radio+%28Culture%29%2CMargaret+Thatcher%2CJeremy+Vine%2CPolitics%2CBBC%2CRadio+2%2CRadio+4%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Miranda+Sawyer&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+10%3A50&c8=1895877&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Rewind+radio%3A+Jon+Ronson+On%E2%80%A6+Being+Normal%3B+The+Funeral+of+Baroness+Thatcher%3B+Jeremy+Vine+%E2%80%93+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FRadio\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Jon Ronson's attempt to define 'normality' came just as the country was determinedly acting abnormally, with the funeral of Baroness Thatcher</p><p><strong>Jon Ronson On… Being Normal</strong> (R4) | <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rw4q3\" title=\"\">iPlayer</a> <br /><strong>The Funeral of Baroness Thatcher</strong> (R4) | <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s5xrl\" title=\"\">iPlayer</a>  <br /><strong>Jeremy Vine</strong> (R2) | <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rv64d\" title=\"\">iPlayer</a></p><p>There were several moments in last week's <strong>Jon Ronson On… </strong>that made me laugh a lot. Mostly these were provided by the very funny Adam Buxton confessing to major anger outbursts, when he goes \"intercontinental ballistic\", gives it \"my best Brian Blessed hairdryer\". One such outburst was triggered by his wife and kids messing up the cutlery drawer – \"spoons placed willy-nilly!\" – so that he couldn't find his favourite cereal spoon.</p><p>\"You have a favourite cereal spoon?\" said Ronson, wonderingly. Which is what he does. He wonders at, and about, people and tells them he is doing so. They respond well.</p><p>Last week's programme was on being normal, coincidentally Ronson's specialist area of inquiry. He will approach the maddest of madmen and wonder at them so hard that they relax and reveal themselves as less mad, less big, more ordinary and… normal.</p><p>The backbone of the programme was the American<em> </em><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagnostic_and_Statistical_Manual_of_Mental_Disorders\" title=\"\"><em>Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders</em></a>, a publication that attempts to define, medically, what is normal behaviour and what is not. The manual gets bigger with every edition, as more and more human behaviour is defined as abnormal. Buxton's sudden rages look as though they fall under 2013's new category of \"intermittent explosive disorder\", which sounds a bit like what Johnny Fartpants suffered from, but is actually supposed to be a definition of extreme – as opposed to everyday – anger.</p><p>Buxton has become not normal. Should we worry? Ronson was definitely concerned. But then, he said, he himself never gets massively angry. His son, Joel, agreed.</p><p>\"You're not a big shouter,\" he said. \"But you're a big bad viber.\"</p><p>\"Passive aggressive!\" yelped Buxton.</p><p>\"The best type of aggressive,\" said Ronson.</p><p>All a bit of a hoot. But then Ronson talked to a couple of others, including Alex Trenchard, who set up a music festival and paid for it with his corporate credit card. Trenchard worked for Tesco and racked up £355,000 of debts. <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-12358495\" title=\"\">He went to prison</a>, where the only thing that kept him going was the idea that he could do the festival again when he got out. Was his obsession normal? How could it be, when it ended with him in prison? And yet, how can it be abnormal, given that every business person will tell you that the only way any venture gets off the ground is for you to be completely obsessive about it?</p><p>Speaking of obsessions, shall we turn to the funeral? I deliberately didn't write about any Thatcher tributes in last weekend's column, figuring that you'd have enough newsprint and TV to wade through. But last Wednesday saw the full stop to our Maggie obsession, surely. Surely? \"We're all Thatcherites now,\" said Cameron to John Humphrys, who politely refrained from snorting.</p><p>Radio 4 gave over two hours of its morning schedule to the funeral procession and service. We were, said a suitably sombre Sian Williams, at \"the heart of political and ceremonial London\". Such a place seemed far, far away from everyone else in the country; over the rainbow, in the Land of Media and Westminster Oz. Still, Radio 4's coverage struck the right tone, with Jim Naughtie bringing his twinkle to proceedings. The funeral rambled on in the background like a Test match, with none of the extreme emotion that has made the last fortnight unbearable.</p><p>Afterwards I switched to <strong>Jeremy Vine</strong>. The emotion was still there. Listeners told of being made redundant, then setting up their own business, buying their council houses, selling them, moving to a nice area. They spoke of going to the funeral, described its \"good, patriotic atmosphere\". And one woman described how her 17-year-old son committed suicide in the 80s \"because he felt he could not live under that particular government\".</p><p>I don't think Margaret Thatcher was the Wicked Witch of the East (or West). But she has certainly cast a strange spell over the country these past couple of weeks. I hope that spell has broken and we can all get back to… well, to being normal again. Whatever that is, when it's at home.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/margaretthatcher\">Margaret Thatcher</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/jeremy-vine\">Jeremy Vine</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/bbc\">BBC</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/radio-2\">Radio 2</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/radio4\">Radio 4</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/mirandasawyer\">Miranda Sawyer</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/jon-ronson-on-being-normal-review" (20851 3465) old 16 nil nil ((title nil "Rewind radio: Jon Ronson On… Being Normal; The Funeral of Baroness Thatcher; Jeremy Vine – review") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/jon-ronson-on-being-normal-review") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/35393?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Ajon-ronson-on-being-normal-review%3A1895877&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Obs&c4=Radio+%28Culture%29%2CMargaret+Thatcher%2CJeremy+Vine%2CPolitics%2CBBC%2CRadio+2%2CRadio+4%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture&c5=Unclassified%2CNot+commercially+useful%2CRadio+Media%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Miranda+Sawyer&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+10%3A50&c8=1895877&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Rewind+radio%3A+Jon+Ronson+On%E2%80%A6+Being+Normal%3B+The+Funeral+of+Baroness+Thatcher%3B+Jeremy+Vine+%E2%80%93+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FRadio\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Jon Ronson's attempt to define 'normality' came just as the country was determinedly acting abnormally, with the funeral of Baroness Thatcher</p><p><strong>Jon Ronson On… Being Normal</strong> (R4) | <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rw4q3\" title=\"\">iPlayer</a> <br /><strong>The Funeral of Baroness Thatcher</strong> (R4) | <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s5xrl\" title=\"\">iPlayer</a>  <br /><strong>Jeremy Vine</strong> (R2) | <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01rv64d\" title=\"\">iPlayer</a></p><p>There were several moments in last week's <strong>Jon Ronson On… </strong>that made me laugh