d. Trenchard worked for Tesco and racked up £355,000 of debts. <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-12358495\" title=\"\">He went to prison</a>, where the only thing that kept him going was the idea that he could do the festival again when he got out. Was his obsession normal? How could it be, when it ended with him in prison? And yet, how can it be abnormal, given that every business person will tell you that the only way any venture gets off the ground is for you to be completely obsessive about it?</p><p>Speaking of obsessions, shall we turn to the funeral? I deliberately didn't write about any Thatcher tributes in last weekend's column, figuring that you'd have enough newsprint and TV to wade through. But last Wednesday saw the full stop to our Maggie obsession, surely. Surely? \"We're all Thatcherites now,\" said Cameron to John Humphrys, who politely refrained from snorting.</p><p>Radio 4 gave over two hours of its morning schedule to the funeral procession and service. We were, said a suitably sombre Sian Williams, at \"the heart of political and ceremonial London\". Such a place seemed far, far away from everyone else in the country; over the rainbow, in the Land of Media and Westminster Oz. Still, Radio 4's coverage struck the right tone, with Jim Naughtie bringing his twinkle to proceedings. The funeral rambled on in the background like a Test match, with none of the extreme emotion that has made the last fortnight unbearable.</p><p>Afterwards I switched to <strong>Jeremy Vine</strong>. The emotion was still there. Listeners told of being made redundant, then setting up their own business, buying their council houses, selling them, moving to a nice area. They spoke of going to the funeral, described its \"good, patriotic atmosphere\". And one woman described how her 17-year-old son committed suicide in the 80s \"because he felt he could not live under that particular government\".</p><p>I don't think Margaret Thatcher was the Wicked Witch of the East (or West). But she has certainly cast a strange spell over the country these past couple of weeks. I hope that spell has broken and we can all get back to… well, to being normal again. Whatever that is, when it's at home.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/radio\">Radio</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/margaretthatcher\">Margaret Thatcher</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/jeremy-vine\">Jeremy Vine</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/bbc\">BBC</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/radio-2\">Radio 2</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/radio4\">Radio 4</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/mirandasawyer\">Miranda Sawyer</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Margaret Thatcher") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Jeremy Vine") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Politics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "BBC") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Radio 2") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/media")) "Radio 4") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Observer") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 21:50:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/jon-ronson-on-being-normal-review") (dc:creator nil "Miranda Sawyer") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T23:06:46Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407439763") (media:keywords nil "Radio, Margaret Thatcher, Jeremy Vine, Politics, BBC, Radio 2, Radio 4, Television & radio, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Columnist/Columnists/2013/4/18/1366288073114/Jon-Ronson-005.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Murdo Macleod/Murdo Macleod") (media:description nil "Jon Ronson 'wonders at, and about, people and tells them he is doing so. They respond well.' Photograph: Murdo Macleod")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Columnist/Columnists/2013/4/18/1366288080733/Jon-Ronson-010.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Murdo Macleod/Murdo Macleod") (media:description nil "Jon Ronson 'wonders at, and about, people and tells them he is doing so. They respond well'. Photograph: Murdo Macleod")))) ("Rewind TV: Endeavour; The Ice Cream Girls; The Secret Life of Rockpools – review" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91593?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aendeavour-ice-cream-girls-review%3A1896750&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Obs&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Euan+Ferguson&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+10%3A45&c8=1896750&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Observer+TV+reviews+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Rewind+TV%3A+Endeavour%3B+The+Ice+Cream+Girls%3B+The+Secret+Life+of+Rockpools+%E2%80%93+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FCulture%2FTelevision+%26amp%3B+radio%2FTelevision\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">The young Morse and his mentor made a perfect couple in Endeavour, but The Ice Cream Girls left our reviewer cold</p><p><strong>Endeavour </strong>(ITV1) | <a href=\"https://www.itv.com/itvplayer/endeavour/series-2/episode-1-girl\" title=\"\">ITVplayer</a><br /><a href=\"http://www.icecreamgirls.co.uk/\" title=\"\"><strong>The Ice Cream Girls</strong></a><strong> </strong>(ITV1)<br /><strong>The Secret Life of Rockpools</strong> (BBC4) | <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b01rtdr4/The_Secret_Life_of_Rock_Pools/\" title=\"\">iPlayer</a></p><p>Roger Allam is perfectly suited and booted to play DI Fred Thursday, boss and mentor to the young, not yet inspector, Morse in <strong>Endeavour</strong>,<strong> </strong>ITV's prequel to the classic detective series. It's as if he were never destined to play anything else. Big, jowly, with a well-styled trenchcoat, buffed size 12s and, very presumably, a vest: he inhabits his own skin wonderfully wisely. Lugubrious to the point of torpor, he catches the mood perfectly; if it's not raining it will be soon, and there'll be another damp beer along in a minute.</p><p>As such, he's the perfect foil to Shaun Evans's Endeavour Morse. Coming into his own, he, Endeavour, quite suddenly realises he's cleverer than many, many people, that it's something he will need to live with, but never quite <em>learn</em> to live with. The archetypal outsider, somewhat chippy, delightfully brittle, he reveals himself in great gobbets to his equally troubled superior.</p><p>The one thing we will never be deeply privy to is, oh lord, Morse's women. In time he will be essentially drawn to mad women with scary haircuts, a quietly significant number of murderesses among them.</p><p>But lo! – there has been an entire reinvention. Old Morse was a touch tired, along with Lewis, who, let's face it, increasingly approached a scene-of-crime blithely unbothered whether he was going for a shit or a haircut. But <em>Endeavour </em>– this one will, delightedly, run and run. And along the way we got such esoterica as postal orders, Routemasters, wet weekends in Rhyl, those splendid old green and cream buses, and the gloriously named \"Spanish practices\".</p><p><strong>The Ice Cream Girls </strong>was hard to like. Maybe Dorothy Koomsom's mid-90s novel would have benefited from a few years left mouldering on the shelf. The story – two women return to the town where as teenage friends they were accused of murder – is enticing enough. The acting couldn't be noticeably faulted, whether it was that nice Martin Compston, who slowly revealed himself as a borderline rapist (and not that very much of the borderline about it), or the fabulously unlikable Serena, played by Lorraine Burroughs, or Jodhi May as Poppy, who went about the place looking like another wet weekend in Rhyl yet, somehow, in a good way. Rather, it was the <em>meh</em> factor. With so much purportedly fine drama clogging the airwaves (and it's worth noting that one of those purported, that poor beast&nbsp;<em>Broadchurch, </em>is<em> </em>currently limping on waiting for someone to take an axe to it), this was just another programme you watched while your mind wandered.</p><p>I adored <strong>The Secret Life of Rockpools</strong>, not least the manner in which it was curated. Richard Fortey wears his learning (as a palaeontologist) feather-lightly, which was one of the strengths of this documentary, but that didn't mean he was above inserting the odd fact of fascination, such as: did you know that many of the lifeforms thronging our rockpools are at the very least as old as the hills: that's right, they're <em>older than the dinosaurs</em>.</p><p>Cushion stars, dog whelks, porcelain crabs, and who'd have thought it but under our toes, all these years, were the successors to dinosaurs. It's all to do with the superfine tolerances necessary to adapt to this method of life, that method being by necessity between a rock and a hard place, with stresses so imaginative, so very overwhelming, they make the rest of us look like extreme johnny-come-latelys, which of course by and large we are.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/euanferguson\">Euan Ferguson</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/endeavour-ice-cream-girls-review" (20851 3165) old 17 nil nil ((title nil "Rewind TV: Endeavour; The Ice Cream Girls; The Secret Life of Rockpools – review") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/endeavour-ice-cream-girls-review") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/91593?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Aendeavour-ice-cream-girls-review%3A1896750&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c3=Obs&c4=Television+%28Culture%29%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CDrama+%28TV+genre%29%2CCulture&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CTelevision+Media&c6=Euan+Ferguson&c7=2013%2F04%2F20+10%3A45&c8=1896750&c9=Article&c10=Review&c13=Observer+TV+reviews+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Rewind+TV%3A+Endeavour%3B+The+Ice+Cream+Girls%3B+The+Secret+Life+of+Rockpools+%E2%80%93+review&c66=Culture&c72=&c73=&c74