scene-of-crime blithely unbothered whether he was going for a shit or a haircut. But <em>Endeavour </em>– this one will, delightedly, run and run. And along the way we got such esoterica as postal orders, Routemasters, wet weekends in Rhyl, those splendid old green and cream buses, and the gloriously named \"Spanish practices\".</p><p><strong>The Ice Cream Girls </strong>was hard to like. Maybe Dorothy Koomsom's mid-90s novel would have benefited from a few years left mouldering on the shelf. The story – two women return to the town where as teenage friends they were accused of murder – is enticing enough. The acting couldn't be noticeably faulted, whether it was that nice Martin Compston, who slowly revealed himself as a borderline rapist (and not that very much of the borderline about it), or the fabulously unlikable Serena, played by Lorraine Burroughs, or Jodhi May as Poppy, who went about the place looking like another wet weekend in Rhyl yet, somehow, in a good way. Rather, it was the <em>meh</em> factor. With so much purportedly fine drama clogging the airwaves (and it's worth noting that one of those purported, that poor beast&nbsp;<em>Broadchurch, </em>is<em> </em>currently limping on waiting for someone to take an axe to it), this was just another programme you watched while your mind wandered.</p><p>I adored <strong>The Secret Life of Rockpools</strong>, not least the manner in which it was curated. Richard Fortey wears his learning (as a palaeontologist) feather-lightly, which was one of the strengths of this documentary, but that didn't mean he was above inserting the odd fact of fascination, such as: did you know that many of the lifeforms thronging our rockpools are at the very least as old as the hills: that's right, they're <em>older than the dinosaurs</em>.</p><p>Cushion stars, dog whelks, porcelain crabs, and who'd have thought it but under our toes, all these years, were the successors to dinosaurs. It's all to do with the superfine tolerances necessary to adapt to this method of life, that method being by necessity between a rock and a hard place, with stresses so imaginative, so very overwhelming, they make the rest of us look like extreme johnny-come-latelys, which of course by and large we are.</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/drama\">Drama</a></li></ul></div><div class=\"author\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/euanferguson\">Euan Ferguson</a></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Drama") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/publication")) "The Observer") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tone")) "Reviews") (pubDate nil "Sat, 20 Apr 2013 21:45:01 GMT") (guid nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2013/apr/20/endeavour-ice-cream-girls-review") (dc:creator nil "Euan Ferguson") (dc:subject nil "Television &amp; radio") (dc:date nil "2013-04-20T23:09:11Z") (dc:type nil "Article") (dc:identifier nil "407542359") (media:keywords nil "Television, Television & radio, Drama, Culture") (media:content ((height . "84") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "140") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Observer/Pix/pictures/2013/4/1