:ebu")) "Public domain") (media:description nil "Professor of cardiology Mark Kearney: 'the simple fact is that heart disease remains Britain’s number one killer'.")) (media:content ((height . "276") (type . "image/jpeg") (width . "460") (url . "http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2013/4/20/1366473561277/Mark-Kearney-008.jpg")) (media:credit ((scheme . "urn:ebu")) "Public domain") (media:description nil "Professor of cardiology Mark Kearney: 'the simple fact is that heart disease remains Britain’s number one killer'.")))) ("Comic character stands for parliament in David Miliband's old seat" "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/34989?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Acomic-character-david-miliband-lee-nelson%3A1896774&ch=Politics&c3=G2&c4=Byelections%2CPolitics%2CUK+news%2CDavid+Miliband%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture%2CComedy+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CComedy%2CTelevision+Media&c6=&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+08%3A00&c8=1896774&c9=Blog&c10=Feature&c13=Pass+notes+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c25=Shortcuts&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Comic+character+stands+for+parliament+in+David+Miliband%27s+old+seat&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FPolitics%2FByelections\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Who is this Lee Nelson who is representing the Well Good Party in South Shields?</p><p><strong>Age: </strong>Unknown.</p><p><strong>Appearance: </strong>Baseball-capped, loudmouthed London geezer.</p><p><strong>What about him?</strong> He is standing for parliament in&nbsp;the upcoming byelection in South Shields, David Miliband's old seat.</p><p><strong>Labour, Tory or other?</strong> Decidedly other. He is representing Lee Nelson's Well Good Party.</p><p><strong>Ah, a single-issue crank. What are his policies? </strong>He wants to scrap the euro, ban traffic wardens and make all education voluntary.</p><p><strong>Are you sure he's not a Tory?</strong> He also wants half the cabinet to consist of people who left school at&nbsp;16, and promises to decriminalise crime.</p><p><strong>Is this bloke for real?</strong> No.</p><p><strong>Oh. Isn't he? </strong>No, he's a comic \"chav\" character played by Simon Brodkin, from a series called Lee&nbsp;Nelson's Well Good Show.</p><p><strong>Never seen it. </strong>It ran for two series on BBC3.</p><p><strong>That would explain it. How was it received?</strong> A&nbsp;reviewer for this newspaper described it as&nbsp;\"almost the exact scientific opposite of well&nbsp;good\".</p><p><strong>I try to keep up with the latest developments in&nbsp;election reform, but just remind me: is it now&nbsp;possible for fictional characters to run for&nbsp;parliament?</strong> Probably not, but Nelson has apparently filed his nomination papers and plans to make a speech on the steps of South Shields town hall.</p><p><strong>Why would he do that?</strong> He's in the middle of a standup tour, and has a new show – <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p015bd9k\" title=\"\">Lee Nelson's Well Funny People</a> – running on BBC3.</p><p><strong>So it's just a publicity stunt?</strong> Or possibly part of&nbsp;the show itself. Another character from the series, footballer Jason Bent, was arrested in&nbsp;March for sneaking onto the pitch at Goodison Park to train with Liverpool players before a&nbsp;match.</p><p><strong>Is it now possible to charge fictional characters with crimes?</strong> No, on this occasion it was Brodkin,&nbsp;36, who received a six-month conditional caution.</p><p><strong>Tell me something about Brodkin that will make me like him a little bit. </strong>He's a qualified doctor who gave up medicine for comedy.</p><p><strong>Do say: </strong>\"If it gets young people interested in politics, this stunt's painful unfunniness will have&nbsp;been worth it.\"</p><p><strong>Don't say: </strong>\"First, do no harm.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/byelections\">Byelections</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/davidmiliband\">David Miliband</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />" "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/shortcuts/2013/apr/21/comic-character-david-miliband-lee-nelson" (20852 14139) new 11 nil nil ((title nil "Comic character stands for parliament in David Miliband's old seat") (link nil "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/shortcuts/2013/apr/21/comic-character-david-miliband-lee-nelson") (description nil "<div class=\"track\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-feeds/1/H.25.4/34989?ns=guardian&pageName=Article%3Acomic-character-david-miliband-lee-nelson%3A1896774&ch=Politics&c3=G2&c4=Byelections%2CPolitics%2CUK+news%2CDavid+Miliband%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV%2CCulture%2CComedy+%28TV+genre%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29&c5=Not+commercially+useful%2CComedy%2CTelevision+Media&c6=&c7=2013%2F04%2F21+08%3A00&c8=1896774&c9=Blog&c10=Feature&c13=Pass+notes+%28series%29&c19=GUK&c25=Shortcuts&c47=UK&c64=UK&c65=Comic+character+stands+for+parliament+in+David+Miliband%27s+old+seat&c66=News&c72=&c73=&c74=&c75=&h2=GU%2FNews%2FPolitics%2FByelections\" width=\"1\" height=\"1\" /></div><p class=\"standfirst\">Who is this Lee Nelson who is representing the Well Good Party in South Shields?</p><p><strong>Age: </strong>Unknown.</p><p><strong>Appearance: </strong>Baseball-capped, loudmouthed London geezer.</p><p><strong>What about him?</strong> He is standing for parliament in&nbsp;the upcoming byelection in South Shields, David Miliband's old seat.</p><p><strong>Labour, Tory or other?</strong> Decidedly other. He is representing Lee Nelson's Well Good Party.</p><p><strong>Ah, a single-issue crank. What are his policies? </strong>He wants to scrap the euro, ban traffic wardens and make all education voluntary.</p><p><strong>Are you sure he's not a Tory?</strong> He also wants half the cabinet to consist of people who left school at&nbsp;16, and promises to decriminalise crime.</p><p><strong>Is this bloke for real?</strong> No.</p><p><strong>Oh. Isn't he? </strong>No, he's a comic \"chav\" character played by Simon Brodkin, from a series called Lee&nbsp;Nelson's Well Good Show.</p><p><strong>Never seen it. </strong>It ran for two series on BBC3.</p><p><strong>That would explain it. How was it received?</strong> A&nbsp;reviewer for this newspaper described it as&nbsp;\"almost the exact scientific opposite of well&nbsp;good\".</p><p><strong>I try to keep up with the latest developments in&nbsp;election reform, but just remind me: is it now&nbsp;possible for fictional characters to run for&nbsp;parliament?</strong> Probably not, but Nelson has apparently filed his nomination papers and plans to make a speech on the steps of South Shields town hall.</p><p><strong>Why would he do that?</strong> He's in the middle of a standup tour, and has a new show – <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p015bd9k\" title=\"\">Lee Nelson's Well Funny People</a> – running on BBC3.</p><p><strong>So it's just a publicity stunt?</strong> Or possibly part of&nbsp;the show itself. Another character from the series, footballer Jason Bent, was arrested in&nbsp;March for sneaking onto the pitch at Goodison Park to train with Liverpool players before a&nbsp;match.</p><p><strong>Is it now possible to charge fictional characters with crimes?</strong> No, on this occasion it was Brodkin,&nbsp;36, who received a six-month conditional caution.</p><p><strong>Tell me something about Brodkin that will make me like him a little bit. </strong>He's a qualified doctor who gave up medicine for comedy.</p><p><strong>Do say: </strong>\"If it gets young people interested in politics, this stunt's painful unfunniness will have&nbsp;been worth it.\"</p><p><strong>Don't say: </strong>\"First, do no harm.\"</p><div class=\"related\" style=\"float: left; margin-right: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/byelections\">Byelections</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/davidmiliband\">David Miliband</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/comedy\">Comedy</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/television\">Television</a></li><li><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/comedy\">Comedy</a></li></ul></div><br/><div class=\"terms\"><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk\">guardian.co.uk</a> &copy; 2013 Guardian News and Media Limited or its affiliated companies. All rights reserved. | Use of this content is subject to our <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/terms-of-service\">Terms & Conditions</a> | <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/help/feeds\">More Feeds</a></div><p style=\"clear:both\" />") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Byelections") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "Politics") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk")) "UK news") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics")) "David Miliband") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Television & radio") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture")) "Culture") (category ((domain . "http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio")) "Comedy") (category ((domain 